i.d: Represents the value of highest-quality sources of capital which banks and other financial institutions are required to keep in order to be protected against bankruptcy. Under Basel accords, core Tier 1 capital (Common Equity Tier 1 capital) is defined as the sum of common stockholder’s equity, retained earnings, accumulated other comprehensive income and minority interest, excluding goodwill, intangible assets, deferred tax assets, pension plan assets and other adjustments.

i.d: Represents the value of highest-quality sources of capital which banks and other financial institutions are required to keep in order to be protected against bankruptcy, other than those included in the core Tier 1 capital (the Common Equity Tier 1 capital). Under Basel accords, hybrid Tier 1 capital is defined as the sum of Tier 1 instruments that are not included in the core Tier 1 capital. These include certain instruments included in hybrid Tier 1 capital and share premiums resulting from these instruments, excluding regulatory adjustments.

i.d: Represents the value of high-quality sources of capital which banks and other financial institutions are required to keep in order to be protected against bankruptcy. Under Basel accords, Tier 1 capital is defined as the sum of common stockholder’s equity, retained earnings, certain qualifying issues of subordinated debt, perpetual preferred stock, minority interest, share premiums and certain other instruments, excluding goodwill, intangible assets, deferred tax assets, pension plan assets and other adjustments.
i.i: A:1L A:AN A:AP A:FP A:FR A:FQ A:AQ A:FN A:1W A:31 A:FS A:AR A:32 A:AT A:AU A:33 A:34 A:35 A:36 A:37 A:FU A:FT A:10 A:39 A:3A A:AS A:2R A:BF A:BG A:BH A:BI A:BJ A:3C A:3B A:3F A:1X A:FV A:FX A:FW A:18 A:FZ A:FY A:AV I:17 I:50 A:2X A:KZ A:L0 A:L1 A:L2 A:L3 A:L4 A:L5 A:L6 A:5M A:2Y

i.d: Represents the value of supplemental sources of capital which banks and other financial institutions are required to keep in order to be protected against bankruptcy. Under Basel accords, the Tier 2 capital includes the sources of capital which are subordinated to depositors and the general creditors of a bank such as long-term, non-perpetual subordinated bonds or debt; non-perpetual preferred stock not included in the Tier 1 capital (the nominal value and the share premium); a minority interest in a bank’s subsidiaries which qualifies as the Tier 2 capital; certain loan loss provisions or reserves.

i.d: Represents the value of the Tier 3 capital held by banks to support market, commodities and foreign currency risks. It includes a greater variety of debt than the Tier 1 capital and the Tier 2 capital. The Tier 3 capital is generally encountered in companies reporting under Basel I or Basel II rules. Under Basel III Tier 3 capital has been eliminated, however it will only be phased out gradually (until 2023).

i.d: Represents the value of total net capital sources of financing available to a bank or a financial institution, calculated in accordance with Basel accords or local capital risk regulations. Also referred to as total regulatory capital.

i.d: Represents the value of both on-balance sheet and off-balance sheet assets, weighted for credit and market risks. Each item is assigned a value based upon specific guidelines designed to evaluate the risk associated with the underlying asset. The risk-weighted capital is also referred to as total risk-weighted assets, or total risk-adjusted assets.

i.d: Represents the ratio of core Tier 1 capital as a percentage of total risk-weighted assets. It is collected as reported by a company, or calculated as TR.CapitalAdequacyValueCoreTier1Capital divided by TR.TotalRiskWeightedCapital. The ratio represents the highest-quality sources of capital which banks and other financial institutions are required to keep in order to be protected against bankruptcy. It is also referred to as the Common Equity Tier 1 (CET1) capital ratio. Regulatory requirements mandate this ratio to exceed 4.5% starting with 2015.

i.d: Represents the ratio of Tier 1 capital as a percentage of total risk-weighted assets. The ratio represents high-quality sources of capital which banks and other financial institutions are required to keep in order to be protected against bankruptcy. It is also referred to as the core capital ratio, or as the going-concern capital ratio. Regulatory requirements mandate this ratio to exceed 6% starting with 2015.

i.d: Represents the ratio of Tier 2 capital as a percentage of total risk-weighted assets. It represents supplemental sources of capital which banks and other financial institutions are required to keep in order to be protected against bankruptcy. It may also be referred to as the supplementary capital ratio, or as the gone-concern capital ratio.

The Tier 3 capital ratio is generally encountered in companies reporting under Basel I or Basel II rules.

i.d: Represents the ratio of total regulatory capital as a percentage of total risk-weighted assets. The total capital ratio includes all net capital sources of financing available to a bank or a financial institution, calculated in accordance with Basel accords or local capital risk regulations. It is a measure showing a company’s maximum ability to absorb losses in the occurrence of a market stress. It may also be referred to as: the total regulatory capital ratio, the total eligible capital ratio, the total risk asset ratio, the capital adequacy ratio, the equity funds ratio and the solvency ratio. Regulatory requirements typically mandate this ratio to exceed 8%.

It shows the extent to which a financial institution’s total risk exposures are covered by a high-quality portion of its capital. Basel III accords require this ratio to exceed 3%.

The ratio shows a company’s ability to fund long-term assets with a minimum amount of stable liabilities. Basel III accords require this ratio to exceed 100%.

Basel III accords require this ratio to exceed 100%.

i.d: Private Company. Accumulated Amortization & Impairment - Goodwill [AAGA] represents the total accumulated impairment or amortization of positive goodwill. This is used when the company reports positive goodwill separately. Applicable to all industries. Accumulated Amortization & Impairment - Goodwill [AAGA] includes: • Cost in excess of assets purchased • Impairment relating to goodwill reported under the movements table Accumulated Amortization & Impairment - Goodwill [AAGA] excludes: • Amortization/impairment of negative goodwill (Accumulated Amortization Negative Goodwill [ANGA])

i.d: Private Company. Accumulated Depreciation - Investment Property [ADID] represents accumulated depreciation and impairment of investment property. Investment property is a property (land or a building, or part of a building or both) held to earn rentals or for capital appreciation purposes. Depending on accounting standards, these can be reported either in the table of tangible assets or separately. Thomson Reuters treat investment properties as a separate category from tangible assets, using investment property codes. Either the face value of investment properties reported at Cost or at Fair value is collected. In the U.S. and other markets, investment properties can also be called income producing property. Applicable to all industries. Accumulated Depreciation - Investment Property [ADID] includes: • Accumulated depreciation and impairment of investment property, even if reported in the table of tangible assets, in the U.S. and other markets • Accumulated depreciation and impairment of commercial real estate that earns rental income Accumulated Depreciation - Investment Property [ADID] excludes: • Accumulated depreciation and impairment of buildings held for own use, Accumulated Depreciation/Impairment Buildings in the table of tangible assets (Acc Depr Buildings [ADPB]) • Property under construction or development, intended for sale in the ordinary course of business (Inventories - Non-Current [ANIN]) • Accumulated depreciation on property constructed/developed on behalf of third parties as part of a construction contract (Accumulated Depreciation Other Tangible Fixed Assets [ADOP]) • Fair value of investment property if reported in notes (Fair Value of Investment Property [AFVP])

i.d: Private Company. Accounts & Notes Receivable - Trade, Net [SANT] represents the total value of receivables from the sales of products, goods, trading assets (such as inventories) or from services provided, before provisions for doubtful receivables. It includes value of receivables from subsidiaries, affiliates, associates, joint ventures or other companies forming the same capital group, unbilled utility revenue. This item is applicable to non-differentiated balance sheet. Applicable to Industrial and Other Financial companies. Accounts and Notes Receivable - Trade, Net [SANT] includes: • Trade receivables (net of the provision for doubtful accounts) • Accounts receivable (net of the provision for doubtful accounts) • Non-interest earning factored/factoring receivables • Rent receivable in real estate operations companies • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries, if clearly described as trade receivables or reported within trade receivables • Advisory fees receivable in investment service companies • Royalty/franchise fees receivable in franchising businesses • Unbilled Receivables (for non-utility Industrial companies, if reported under Receivables or as a separate line item) • Long-term trade receivables (net of provision for doubtful accounts) • Long-term accounts receivable (net of provision for doubtful accounts) • Non-interest earning factored/factoring receivables • Rent receivable in real estate operations companies (net of provision for doubtful accounts) • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries, if clearly described as trade receivables or reported within trade receivables • Advisory fees receivable in investment service companies • Royalty/franchise fees receivable in franchising businesses • Long-term unbilled receivables • Unbilled utility revenue for utility companies (Current Unbilled Utility Revenue - Net/Gross [AUUR]) ccounts and Notes Receivable - Trade, Net [SANT] excludes: • Receivables from employees, officers, directors (Other Non-Current Receivables, Net [ALON]) • Long-term receivables from financial/capitalized lease contracts (Long Term Finance Lease Receivables, Net [ALFL]) • Long-term loans, notes receivable and interest-earning receivables other than arising from financial leases (Loans/Notes Receivables, Gross - Net/Gross [AOTX]) • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries, if reported outside trade receivables (Other Receivables, Net [AORC]) • Loans, notes receivable and interest-earning receivables other than arising from financial leases (Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ACLR]) • Current receivables from financial/capitalized lease contracts (Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ACLR]) • Receivables from stockholders (Other Receivables, Net [AORC]) • Current receivables from Islamic financing contracts (Islamic Receivables, Current [ISRC]) • Short-Term loans to employees, officers, directors and affiliates, before loan loss provisions (Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ACLR])

Accounts Payable [LAPB] represents amounts payable/owed to creditors or suppliers for materials and merchandise acquired or for services provided within the normal operations of the business. Applicable to all industries. Accounts Payable [LAPB] includes: • Trade creditors for the goods and services provided • Accounts payable to joint ventures, partnerships • Bills Payable reported as part of Trade/Accounts Payable • Payable to/due to related parties, affiliates and associates, when reported within trade payables Accounts Payable [LAPB] excludes: • Payables towards Income taxes (Income Taxes Payable [LTXP]) • Payables towards dividends (common or preferred) (Dividends & Distributions Payable [LDPB]) • Payables towards rent or any other expenses (Accrued Expenses [LCAE]) • Expenses such as interest accrued/payable (Interest Payable - Short Term debt [LSIP]) • Accrued expenses such as wages/salaries accrued/payable, accrued compensation to employees (Accrued Payroll [LCAP]) • Bills of exchange and notes payable (ST Debt & Notes Payable [LSOD]) • Short-term debt payable (ST Debt & Notes Payable [LSOD]) • Accounts payable combined with accrued expenses (Payable/Accrued [LPBA]) • Payable to/due to related parties, affiliates and associates, when not reported within trade payables (Other Payables [LOPB])

i.d: Private Company. Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR] represents claims held against customers for goods sold or services rendered. Applicable to Industrial, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR] includes: • Trade receivables (net of the provision for doubtful accounts) • Accounts receivable (net of the provision for doubtful accounts) • Non-interest earning factored/factoring receivables • Rent receivable in real estate operations companies • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries, if clearly described as trade receivables or reported within trade receivables • Advisory fees receivable in investment service companies • Royalty/franchise fees receivable in franchising businesses • Unbilled Receivables (for non-utility Industrial companies, if reported under Receivables or as a separate line item) Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR] excludes: • Receivables from employees, officers, directors (Other Receivables, Net [AORC]) • Taxes receivable (Income Tax Receivables - Net/Gross [AOTX]) • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries, if reported outside trade receivables (Other Receivables, Net [AORC]) • Loans, notes receivable and interest-earning receivables other than arising from financial leases (Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ACLR]) • Current receivables from financial/capitalized lease contracts (Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ACLR]) • Receivables from stockholders (Other Receivables, Net [AORC]) • Unbilled utility revenue for utility companies (Current Unbilled Utility Revenue - Net/Gross [AUUR]) • Current receivables from Islamic financing contracts (Islamic Receivables, Current [ISRC]) • Short-Term loans to employees, officers, directors and affiliates, before loan loss provisions (Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ACLR])

i.d: Private Company. Accrued Expenses [SAEA] represents expenses accrued, but not yet paid reported within current liabilities. Applicable to Industrial, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. Accrued Expenses [SAEA] includes: • Accrued expenses, when not included in more specific categories such as accrued payroll, dividends, interest payable, and income tax payable • Payroll taxes • Sales Tax • Taxes other than income taxes • Property taxes • Excise taxes • General & Service taxes • Ad Valorem • Commission (not relating to employees or when the company is silent) • Long-term accrued expenses such as wages/salaries accrued/payable, accrued compensation to employees, social security obligations • Other accrued expenses reported within long-term liabilities • Accrued payroll • Payroll taxes payable • Accrued compensation expenses • Accrued profit sharing • Commission (relating to employees) • Accrued bonus • Vacation pay • Social security obligations Accrued Expenses [SAEA] excludes: • (Trade) accounts payable to suppliers or other trade parties (Accounts Payable [LAPB]) • Accrued expenses such as interest accrued/payable (Interest Payable - Short Term Debt [LSIP]) • Accrued/expenses payable towards income taxes (Income Taxes Payable [LTXP]) • Dividends payable (common or preferred) (Dividends & Distributions Payable [LDPB]) • Notes payable and short-term debt liabilities (ST Debt & Notes Payable [LSOD]) • Deferred income tax –current (Deferred Income Tax - Current Liability [LDTC]) • Accrued interest (Interest Payable - Short Term Debt [LSIP]) • Trade accounts payable to suppliers or other payables (Long Term Trade Payables [LLTP]) • Accrued pension, post-retirement and healthcare benefits (Non-Current Postemployment Benefits - Pensions and Other [LPEN]) • Interest accrued/payable (Interest Payable - Short Term Debt [LSIP]) • Deferred income taxes payable (Deferred Taxation [LBDT], Deferred Tax (Debit) - Liability [LDTF], Deferred Tax Credit - Liability [LDTE], Net Deferred Tax Liability [LDTN]) • Long-term debt, bills of exchange and notes payable (LT Debt excl. Capitalized Leases [LLTD])

Accrued Payroll [LCAP] includes: • Accrued payroll • Payroll taxes payable • Accrued compensation expenses • Accrued profit sharing • Commission (relating to employees) • Accrued bonus • Vacation pay • Social security obligations Accrued Payroll [LCAP] excludes: • Payables towards rent or any other expenses (Accrued Expenses [LCAE]) • Expenses such as interest accrued/payable (Interest Payable - Short Term Debt [LSIP]) • Accounts payable combined with accrued expenses (Payable/Accrued [LPBA]) • Payable to/due to related parties, affiliates and associates, when not reported within trade payables (Other Payables [LOPB]) • Accrued Commissions apart from those relating to employees or when the company is silent (Accrued Expenses [LCAE])

i.l: Additional Paid in Capital - Common Stock (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. Additional Paid in Capital - Common Stock [QPIC] represents the excess amount paid by an investor over the par-value price of a stock issue. Additional paid-in-capital can arise from issuing either preferred or common stock. Collect it under QPIC when capital surplus is reported as a combined value. Applicable to all industries. Additional Paid in Capital – Common Stock [QPIC] excludes: • Capital Surplus on Preferred Stock [QPFS] When we have combined value reported for common stock and additional paid in capital, we need to arrive at the value of common stock by multiplying issued shares by par value. Additional paid in capital is arrived at by deducting the value of common stock arrived at from the reported combined value.

i.l: Additional Paid in Capital incl Opt Rsrve - Comn Stock (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. Additional Paid in Capital incl. Option Reserve - Common Stock [SPIC] represents the excess amount paid by an investor over the par-value price of a stock issue. Additional paid-in-capital can arise from issuing either preferred or common stock. It includes the share option reserves reported by the company. This includes share option reserve, stock and warrant reserves and may be reported under reserves (mainly IFRS) or under additional paid in capital (mainly US-GAAP). Applicable to all industries. Additional Paid in Capital incl. Option Reserve - Common Stock [SPIC] includes: • Share option reserve • Warrant reserve • Additional Paid in Capital - Common Stock [QPIC] Additional Paid in Capital incl. Option Reserve - Common Stock [SPIC] excludes: • Capital Surplus on Preferred Stock [QPFS]

Applicable to all industries.

Buildings, Gross [SBCG] includes: • Mining facilities, oil and natural gas wells and rigs, drilling and extraction facilities • Houses • Revaluation of buildings • Foreign currency transaction Buildings, Gross [SBCG] excludes: • Mining, drilling and extraction equipment (Plant/Machinery/Equipment, Gross [AMEC]) • Land and buildings combined (Land & Buildings, Gross [ALSC]) • Power plants and other utility facilities (Utility Plant, Gross [AUTP]) • Buildings held under capitalized lease or hire-purchase agreements (Property, Plant and Equipment Under Capital Lease, Gross [ACLC]) • Investment properties at cost, even if reported in the table of tangible assets (Investment Property, Gross [ADIC])

i.d: Private Company. Cash & Equivalents [SCAE] represents short-term, highly liquid investments that are both readily convertible to known amounts of cash and so close to their maturity that they present insignificant risk of changes in interest rates. Only investments with original maturities of three months or less qualify under these definitions. Applicable to all industries. Cash & Equivalents [SCAE] includes: • Cash • Cash in Post Office Accounts • Cash in bank • Cash at bank and in hand • Cash on deposits and demand deposits • Cash in transit • Petty cash • Fixed/term deposits and other short term bank deposits, when maturity is less than three months • Cash and Deposits at amortized cost • Deposits with financial service companies other than commercial banks • Short-term paper and CD’s (maturity less than 3 months) • Money market funds • Liquid assets • Cash, when combined with highly liquid Investments Cash & Equivalents [SCAE] excludes: • Fixed/term deposits and other short term bank deposits, when maturity is between 3 and 12 months (ST Investments [ASTI]) • Restricted Cash (Restricted Accounts – Current [ARCA]) • Cash in Transit (Restricted Accounts – Current [ARCA]) • Receivables from sales (Accounts Receivable, Gross [AARG] or Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR]) • Travel advances (Other Receivables, Net [AORC]) Cash [ACSH] excludes: • Cash Due from Banks (Balance with Central Banks [ABCB]) • Cash Due from Employees (Other Receivables, Net [AORC]) • Cash Due from Third Party (accounts receivable or other receivables, depending on the nature of cash due) • Restricted Cash [ARCA – Current or ARCL – Long Term] • Cash in Trust (“Trust” is treated the same way as “Restricted”) [ARCA – Current or ARCL – Long Term] • Short –term investment securities and certificates of deposit (CD’s), when maturity is 3 to 12 months (ST Investments [ASTI]) • Travel advances (Other Receivables, Net [AORC])

i.l: Cash & ST Deposits Due from Banks (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. Cash & Short Term Deposits Due from Banks [SCDB] represents short-term, highly liquid investments that are both readily convertible to known amounts of cash and so close to their maturity that they present insignificant risk of changes in interest rates. It includes cash on hand, balances on demand deposits and near-term savings and time deposits as well as notes and bills receivable by a bank. Applicable to banks. Cash & Short Term Deposits Due from Banks [SCDB] includes: • Fixed/term deposits and other short term bank deposits, when maturity is less than three months • Cash and Deposits at amortized cost • Deposits with financial service companies other than commercial banks • Short-term paper and CD’s (maturity less than 3 months) • Money market funds • Liquid assets • Cash, when combined with highly liquid Investments • Cash, when listed separately on the balance sheet (Cash [ACSH]) • Petty Cash (Cash [ACSH]) • Cash on Deposits (Cash [ACSH]) • Treasury bills (‘T-bills’) • Treasury notes • Trade bills • Money market assets • Commercial papers • Municipal notes • Promissory notes Cash & Short Term Deposits Due from Banks [SCDB] excludes: • Fixed/term deposits and other short term bank deposits, when maturity is between 3 and 12 months (ST Investments [ASTI]) • Restricted Cash (Restricted Accounts – Current [ARCA]) • Cash in Transit (Restricted Accounts – Current [ARCA]) • Receivables from sales (Accounts Receivable, Gross [AARG] or Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR]) • Travel advances (Other Receivables, Net [AORC]) • Cash and Short Term Deposits Due from Banks [XCDU] • Interbank loans receivable (Inter-Bank Loans, Gross [AGLB] or Inter-Bank Loans, Net [ANLB]) • Time Deposits [ABTD] • Securities Purchased under REPOs and Federal Funds Sold [XCOF] • Securities Purchased under REPOs [ACSF] • Certificates of deposit (Time Deposits [ABTD]) • Inter- Bank Lending and Long Term Deposits Due from Banks [ADBU] • Notes receivable reported by Industrial and Property companies (Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ACLR])

Cash & Equivalents, Total [SCASH] represents short-term, highly liquid investments that are both readily convertible to known amounts of cash and so close to their maturity that they present insignificant risk of changes in interest rates. Only investments with original maturities of three months or less qualify under these definitions. Applicable to all industries. Cash & Equivalents, Total [SCASH] includes: • Cash & Cash Equivalents [SCAE] • Cash & ST Deposits Due from Banks – Total [SCDK]

Cash & Interest Bearing Securities [SCAIBS] represents the value of cash and short term investments (Cash & Short Term Investments--Total [SCSTI]) less, if reported, the value of all liabilities arising from Islamic debt financing agreements (Total Islamic Debt [SISD]). In banks this item includes the total value of all borrowings reported by the company (Total Debt [SLSD]). Applicable to all industries.

i.d: Private Company. Cash [ACSH] represents cash on hand, balances on demand deposits and near-term savings and time deposits. These should be readily available for use and must be free from any contractual restrictions that limit their use in satisfying debts and other operational cash needs. Applicable to all industries. Cash [ACSH] includes: • Cash • Cash in Post Office Accounts • Cash in bank • Cash at bank and in hand • Cash on deposits and demand deposits • Cash in transit • Petty cash Cash [ACSH] excludes: • Cash Due from Banks (Balance with Central Banks [ABCB]) • Cash Due from Employees (Other Receivables, Net [AORC]) • Cash Due from Third Party (accounts receivable or other receivables, depending on the nature of cash due) • Time deposits in banks due within 90 days (Cash & Equivalents [ACAE]) • Restricted Cash [ARCA – Current or ARCL – Long Term] • Cash in Trust (“Trust” is treated the same way as “Restricted”) [ARCA – Current or ARCL – Long Term] • Short –term investment securities and certificates of deposit (CD’s), when maturity is less than 3 months (Cash & Equivalents [ACAE]) • Short –term investment securities and certificates of deposit (CD’s), when maturity is 3 to 12 months (ST Investments [ASTI]) • Money Market Funds (Cash & Equivalents [ACAE]) • Travel advances (Other Receivables, Net [AORC])

i.l: Common Equity Attrib to Parent Shareholders (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. Common Equity Attributable to Parent Shareholders [QCEP] represents sum of all capital surpluses on common stock as well as all share option reserves reported by the company (Additional Paid in Capital Including Option Reserve - Common Stock [SPIC]) and the par or stated value of the issued common shares of the company (Issued and Paid - Common Stock [SCMS]) adjusted by the value of common stock owned by the issuing company or its consolidated subsidiaries. Applicable to all industries. Common Equity Attributable to Parent Shareholders [QCEP] includes: • Share option reserve • Warrant reserve • Additional Paid in Capital - Common Stock [QPIC] • Beneficiary interest units or beneficiary shares in REIT • Redeemable common stock, partially paid shares • Multiple voting, basic voting, or no voting common stock • Par value or no par value stock • Shares that do or do not trade on exchanges • Participative preferred stock in certain countries • Shares in process of issuing • Restricted common, reorganized common • Subordinated unit holders • Trust shares/units/corpus • Limited partners’ capital (Limited Partner [QLPD]) • Common Shares Held in ESOP or Trust /Deferred Compensation [SCST] • Own stock in treasury • Reacquired common stock/beneficiary interest unit/limited partnership units • Own Shares held by subsidiaries, trustee, escrow • Treasury stock reported with positive value Common Equity Attributable to Parent Shareholders [QCEP] excludes: • Shares authorized but not yet issued • General partners’ capital (General Partner [QGPD]) • Capital Surplus on Preferred Stock [QPFS]

Current Accruals [SACRU] represents the difference between the value of all current assets (Total Current Assets [STCA]), sum of a company's short term/current liabilities (due within one year) (Current Liabilities - Total [SCLT]), represents the total value of cash on hand and short term deposits due from other banks (Cash & ST Deposits Due from Banks - Total [SCDK]) and the value of short-term, highly liquid investments that are both readily convertible to known amounts of cash and so close to their maturity that they present insignificant risk of changes in interest rates (Cash & Cash Equivalents [SCAE]). i.d: Private Company. Current Accrued Expenses [SAEC] represents expenses accrued, but not yet paid reported within current liabilities. Applicable to Industrial, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. Deferred Costs, Net [ADFN] includes the net value (after amortization and impairment) of: • Deferred operating expenses/charges • Deferred formation expenses, start-up costs and pre-operating costs • Deferred stock issuing costs, bond issuing costs, bond discounts • Deferred plant rearrangement and reinstallation costs • Deferred leasing costs (costs associated with the origination of leasing contracts that are amortized over time) • Deferred financing costs • Deferred tenant incentives/inducements Deferred Costs, Net [ADFN] excludes: • Deferred charges combined with prepayments (Other Deferred Charges/Prepayments [AODC]) • Deferred fuel costs in gas utility companies (gas distributed but not yet charged to customers) (Current Unbilled Utility Revenue - Net/Gross [AUUR]) • Long-Term deferred fuel costs (Non-Current Deferred Fuel Costs [ALDF]) • Long term prepayments (Non-Current Prepaid Expenses [ANPY])

i.d: Private Company. Deferred Income Tax [SDTT] represents deferred tax credits and debits liabilities reported in the asset section. This item includes both short term and long term deferred tax. Applicable to all industries. Deferred Income Tax [SDTT] includes: • Long-term deferred tax credits (liabilities), decreasing the value of deferred taxes receivable or increasing tax liabilities, reported in an asset footnotes • Deferred tax credits (liabilities) reported in an asset footnote, representing a sum of current and non-current assets – collected in the non-differentiated balance sheet format only • Long-term net deferred tax assets, i.e. long-term deferred tax debits (assets) offset with long-term deferred tax credits (liabilities) • Net deferred taxes that represent a sum of current and non-current assets – collected in the non-differentiated balance sheet format only • Long-term deferred tax debits (assets), increasing the value of deferred taxes receivable and decreasing tax liabilities • Deferred tax debits (assets) that represent a sum of current and non-current assets – collected in the non-differentiated balance sheet format only • Current deferred income tax Deferred Income Tax [SDTT] excludes: • Long-term deferred tax credits (liabilities), decreasing the value of deferred taxes receivable or increasing tax liabilities, reported within liabilities or in a liability footnote (Deferred Tax Credit – Liability [LDTE]) • Long-term net deferred tax liabilities, i.e. long-term deferred tax debits (liabilities) offset with deferred tax credits (assets) (Net Deferred Tax Liability [LDTN]) • Short-term deferred tax assets (Deferred Income Tax - Current Asset [ADTC]) • Deferred tax credits (liabilities) reported in an asset footnote, representing a sum of current and non-current assets – not collected in the differentiated balance sheet format • Prepaid taxes when it is differentiated from estimated deferred tax assets (Prepaid Expenses [APPY] when assets of a company are not delineated between current and non-current, otherwise as Other Long-Term Assets [AOLA] • Taxes recoverable • Income taxes recoverable, income tax benefits, taxes refundable (Receivables – Other [AORC]) • Assets when not delineated between current and non-current, all deferred income tax assets are classified as Deferred Income Tax – Long Term Asset [ADTA].

It includes deferred tax debits (assets) and deferred tax credits (liabilities) reported in a liability section. Applicable to all industries. Deferred Income Tax, LT Liability [SDTL] is a sum of • Deferred Tax (Debit) – Liability [LDTF] • Deferred Tax Credit – Liability [LDTE] • Deferred Taxation [LBDT]

i.d: Private Company. Deferred Income Tax & Investment Tax Credits - Non-current [SDTX] represents the the total value of non-current deferred taxes disclosed in the liability section. Applicable to all industries. In differentiated balance sheet Deferred Income Tax & investment Tax Credits - Non-current [SDTX] is a sum of: • Deferred Tax Liability in Untaxed Reserves [SDUR • Deferred Income Tax, LT Liability [SDTL] In non-differentiated balance sheet Deferred Income Tax & investment Tax Credits - Non-current [SDTX] is a sum of: • Deferred Tax Liability in Untaxed Reserves [SDUR] • Deferred Income Tax, LT Liability [SDTL] • Deferred Income Tax - Current Liability [SDTC]

Private Company. Deferred Revenue / Income [SRDI] represents the income received in advance for the goods or services which have not been delivered. Applicable to Investment, Other Financial, Banks and Insurance companies. Deferred Revenue / Income [SRDI] includes: • Advance payments for products and services, received from customers • Customer deposits/prepayments • Unearned income/unearned revenue/deferred revenue • Prepaid income • Fees received but not yet earned • A combination of deferred income, customer advances, billings in excess of costs, or security deposits
Deferred Revenue / Income [SRDI] excludes: • Security deposits received to offset potential losses and as a prove of intent (not related to sales of products or services to be rendered) (Security Deposits [LSED]) • Advance billings to customers in excess of projects completed (Billings in Excess of Cost - Current [LBEX])

i.d: Private Company. Deferred Tax Asset, Net [ADTN] represents net long-term deferred taxes disclosed on the asset side, i.e. long-term deferred tax credits (assets) offset with long-term deferred tax debits (liabilities). Applicable to all industries. Deferred Tax Asset, Net [ADTN] includes: • Long-term net deferred tax assets, i.e. long-term deferred tax debits (assets) offset with long-term deferred tax credits (liabilities) • Net deferred taxes that represent a sum of current and non-current assets – collected in the non-differentiated balance sheet format only Deferred Tax Asset, Net [ADTN] excludes: • Deferred Tax Asset – LT (Deferred Tax Asset - Long Term [ADTA])

i.d: Private Company. Deferred Taxation [LBDT] refers to any long-term deferred taxes disclosed in the liability section, not specified as net deferred taxes, deferred tax credits (liabilities) or deferred tax debits (assets). Applicable to all industries. Deferred Taxation [LBDT] includes: • Long-term deferred tax liabilities not specified as net values or credits/debits Deferred Taxation [LBDT] excludes: • Deferred tax credits (liabilities) reported in a liability section [LDTE] • Long-term net deferred tax liabilities, i.e. long-term deferred tax credits (liabilities) offset with long-term deferred tax debits (assets) [LDTN]) • Long-term deferred tax debits (assets) reported in a liability [LDTF]) • Short-term deferred tax liabilities [LDTC] • Income taxes payable [LTXP]

This is used when the resultant difference (goodwill) is positive. Applicable to all industries. Goodwill, Gross [AGWG] includes: • Cost in excess of assets purchased Goodwill, Gross [AGWG] excludes: • Negative Goodwill, Gross (Negative Goodwill, Gross [ANGG])

i.d: Private Company. Goodwill, Net [AGWN] represents the net book value of goodwill after deduction of accumulated amortization. The net value is the difference between the cost of an acquired entity and the aggregate value of its identifiable assets. When the company reports goodwill net of accumulated amortization, the net figure is directly updated to Goodwill, net and Goodwill, gross and accumulated amortization of goodwill will not be used. Applicable to all industries Goodwill, Net [AGWN] includes: • Accumulated impairment of goodwill • Cost in excess of net assets purchased Goodwill, Net [AGWN] excludes: • Negative goodwill, net (Negative Goodwill, Net [ANGN])

i.d: Private Company. Inventories - Finished Goods [SIFG] represents items purchased for sale, consignment goods sent out to retail store and inventories of unsold finished goods on hand. These goods may have been produced internally or purchased for resale. Applicable to Industrial, Property and Investment companies. Inventories - Finished Goods [SIFG] includes: • Finished Goods • Merchandise in transit • Any item that is available for sale • Iron ore in metal mining companies • Coal in coal mining companies • Gold bullion in gold mining companies • Oil extracted in oil and gas exploration companies • Unbilled revenue (services rendered) in companies other than utility companies, if reported within inventories • Short-term broadcast rights • Program and film rights • Raw stock-tapes Inventories - Finished Goods [SIFG] excludes: • Items that are purchased for own use and capitalized as tangible assets (specific types of property, plant and equipment) • Natural gas in storage for gas utility companies (Gas in Storage – Inventory [AGIS]) • Unbilled receivables reported under Trade Receivables (Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR] or Accounts Receivable, Gross [AARG]) • Biological assets for sale reported by farming and forestry companies (Biological Assets [AIBA]) • Finished development properties for sale (Real Estate Inventory [AIRT])

i.d: Private Company. Inventories – Raw Materials [SIRM] represents raw materials acquired, but not yet used and may also include raw materials in transit. It is limited to materials that are used for manufacturing of finished goods that are eventually sold to customers. Applicable to Industrial, Property and Investment companies. Inventories – Raw Materials [SIRM] includes: • Materials and supplies • Raw Materials and supplies • Leaf tobacco in tobacco companies • Spare parts/ supplies/materials used for manufacturing products for sale • Coffee beans in the food processing industry • Timber already cut in the forestry and wood products industry • Crude oil extracted in the oil and gas industry • Temporary establishments • Real estate under development for sale to external clients • Building lots • Finished/unfinished buildings/housing • Investment properties held for sale • Fuel (coal, oil and gas) in electric utility companies • Fuel in storage Inventories – Raw Materials [SIRM] excludes: • Supplies/materials/parts for own use (such as supplies for plant and equipment) (Other Tangible Fixed Assets, Gross [AOPC] when reported as a part of fixed assets or Other Current Assets [ACAO)] when reported as current assets, but not as inventory) • Biological Assets (Livestock, trees, plants, bushes, vines) (Biological Assets [AIBA]) • Supplies for equipment in cable and broadcasting companies (Other Tangible Fixed Assets, Gross [AOPC] when reported as a part of fixed assets) • Buildings for own use reported within the table of tangible assets (Buildings, Net [APBN]) • Buildings under construction for own use reported within the table of tangible assets (Construction in Progress, Net [ACPN]) • Investment properties (Investment Property, Net [AVPN]) • Tangible assets leased out under operating lease (Property, Plant and Equipment Leased out Operating Lease, Net [APLN]) • Contract receivables from construction work (Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR]) • Nuclear fuel in electric reported part of property, Plant (Utility Plant, Gross [AUTP]) • Deferred fuel costs in gas utility companies (gas distributed but not yet charged to customers) (Current Unbilled Utility Revenue - Net/Gross [AUUR])

Inventories - Work in Progress [SIWP] represents materials acquired for use in the manufacture of products when disclosed combined with products, services or contracts partially completed at a specified time, and not shown separately. i.d: Private Company. Invested Assets & Loans [SINLT] represents the sum of total value of investments (Investments, Total [SINVT]) and the nominal value of loans to customers, before deduction of provisions (Loans, Gross [SLTG]). Applicable to all industries. Invested Assets & Loans [SINLT] includes: • Total gross loans and advances • Total gross loans and advances to non-bank customers • Gross loans held for resale, loans to financial institutions, loans to other companies, consumer loans, mortgage loans, foreign loans and other specific loan types • Total gross lease financing receivables, if combined with total loans • Investments, Total [SINVT] Invested Assets & Loans [SINLT] excludes: • Total loans to customers – net of loan loss provisions (Total Loans to Customers, Net [XNBL]) • Gross interbank loans (Bank Loans, Gross [AGLB]) • Net interbank loans (Bank Loans, Net [ANLB]) • Gross loans to financial institutions other than banks, such as security brokers (Broker/ Financial Institutions Loans, Gross [AGLF]) • Gross loans to non-financial companies, excluding mortgage loans (Commercial/Industrial Loans, Gross [AGLM]) • Mortgage & Property Loans - Commercial & Customer, Gross [AGLP] • Gross capitalised leases and hire-purchase contract receivables (Finance Lease & HP Loans, Gross [AGLH]) • Consumer & Installment Loans, Gross [AGLI] • Gross foreign office loans (Foreign Loans - Commercial, Gross [AGLR]) • Other gross loans to customers (Other Loans to Customers, Gross [ABLO]) • Loans Held for Sale/Resale - Customers [ALHS] • Unearned loan income (Unearned Income - Customers [AUIN]) • Notes receivable (Notes & Bills [ACNO]) • A combination of interbank loans and time deposits receivable (Lending & LT Deposits Due from Banks [ADBU])

i.d: Private Company. Investment Property [SVPT] represents the net book value (after depreciation) of investment property and foreclosed real estate assets reported by a company that uses the historical cost method for the presentation of real estate investments. Investment property is a property (land or a building, or part of a building or both) held to earn rentals or for capital appreciation purposes. Depending on accounting standards, these can be reported either in the table of tangible assets or separately. In TRF, we always treat investment properties as a separate category other than tangible assets, and use investment property codes. Foreclosure is a specific legal process in which a lender attempts to recover the balance of a loan from a borrower who has stopped making payments to the lender by forcing the sale of the asset used as the collateral for the loan. The item is applicable for non-differentiated balance sheet. Investment Property [SVPT] Includes: • Net book value of investment property, even if reported in the table of tangible assets, in the U.S. and other markets • Net book value of commercial real estate earning rental income • Real estate repossessed • Foreclosed real estate • For the U.S., "Other Real Estate Owned" should be used if a company has not provided a more detailed disclosure of foreclosed assets Investment Property [SVPT] Excludes: • Buildings held for own use, classified as Buildings, Gross in the table of tangible assets (APBN) • Property under construction or development, intended for sale in the ordinary course of business (Inventories - Non-current [ANIN]) • Property constructed/developed on behalf of third parties as part of a construction contract • Fair value of investment property (AFVP) • Real estate mortgage loans, which represent loans made by insurance companies to finance construction or the purchase of real estate (classified as AREM) • Real property for own use or for renting (classified as APBC if Gross or APBN if Net)

i.d: Private Company. Investment Property, Gross [ADIC] represents the gross/purchase value of investment properties before deducting accumulated depreciation. Investment property is a property (land or a building, or part of a building or both) held to earn rentals or for capital appreciation purposes. Depending on accounting standards, these can be reported either in the table of tangible assets or separately. Thomson Reuters treat investment properties as a separate category from tangible assets, using investment property codes. Either the face value of investment properties reported at Cost or at Fair value is collected. In the U.S. and other markets, investment properties can also be called income producing property. Applicable to all industries. Investment Property, Gross [ADIC] includes: • Purchase cost of investment property, if reported in the table of tangible assets or as a separate line item • Purchase cost of commercial real estate that earns rental income • Fair value of investment property, reported on face Investment Property, Gross [ADIC] excludes: • Buildings held for own use; Buildings, Gross in the table of tangible assets (Buildings, Gross [APBC]) • Property under construction or development, intended for sale in the ordinary course of business (Inventories - Non-Current [ANIN]) • Property constructed/developed on behalf of third parties as part of a construction contract (Other Tangible Fixed Assets, Net [AOPN]) • Fair value of investment property if reported in notes (Fair Value of Investment Property [AFVP])

i.d: Private Company. Investment Property, Net [AVPN] represents net book value (after depreciation) of investment property. Investment property is a property (land or a building, or part of a building or both) held to earn rentals or for capital appreciation purposes. Depending on accounting standards, these can be reported either in the table of tangible assets or separately. Thomson Reuters treat investment properties as a separate category from tangible assets, using investment property codes. Either the face value of investment properties reported at Cost or at Fair value is collected. In the U.S. and other markets, investment properties can also be called income producing property. Investment Property, Net [AVPN] excludes: • Buildings held for own use in the table of tangible assets (Buildings, Net [APBN]) • Property under construction or development, intended for sale in the ordinary course of business (Inventories - Non-Current [ANIN]) • Property constructed/developed on behalf of third parties as part of a construction contract (Other Tangible Fixed Assets, Net [AOPN]) • Fair value of investment property if reported in notes (Fair Value of Investment Property [AFVP])

i.d: Private Company. Investment Securities [SINVS] represents the value of all securities held for investment purposes. It includes the net change in deposits from customers (liabilities) and an account held at a financial institution and administered by an investment dealer that the account holder uses to employ a trading strategy rather than a buy-and-hold investment strategy. i.l: Investments in Associates, JVs & Unconsol Subs (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. Investments in Associates, Joint Ventures and Unconsolidated Subsidiaries [SEQT] represents investment in associated, affiliated and other companies accounted for by the equity method. Associated companies are usually defined as those where the shareholding company may have a significant influence on decision making in the affiliated company. It usually requires approximately 20% of shareholding to have a significant influence, although the percentage figure is not an absolute criterion. Applicable to all industries. Investments in Associates, Joint Ventures and Unconsolidated Subsidiaries [SEQT] includes: • Equity in affiliates/associates • Investments in affiliated/associated companies • Joint ventures • Investments in unconsolidated subsidiaries Investments in Associates, Joint Ventures and Unconsolidated Subsidiaries [SEQT] excludes: • Amounts due from associates, affiliates, joint ventures, unconsolidated subsidiaries and other related companies, clearly described as trade receivables or reported within trade receivables (Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR]) • Amounts due from associates, affiliates, joint ventures and other related/group companies, reported outside trade receivables (Other Receivables, Net [AORC]) • Loans to associated companies (Non-current Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ALNN]) • Goodwill on acquisition of associated companies (Goodwill, Net [AGWN])

i.d: Private Company. Land & Improvements, Gross [SLIC] represents the gross book value of land and improvements on land at acquisition costs. Land is not depreciated, but land improvements are normally depreciated over time. Applicable to all industries. Land & Improvements, Gross [SLIC] includes: • Land • Land portion of timberland • Logging roads for cutting timber • Freehold land owned by the company • Improvements in freehold land (land owned by the company – subject to depreciation) • Land use rights if reported within PPE break out. • Foreign currency transaction Land & Improvements, Gross [SLIC] excludes: • Land and buildings (Land/Buildings, Gross [ALSC]) • Improvements in leasehold land (Leasehold Improvements, Gross [ALEC]) • Property for sale reported by property developers within long-term assets (Inventories - Non-Current [ANIN]) • Land held for investment purposes in the expectation of value increase (Investment Property, Gross (ADIC), or as Fair Value of Investment Property [AFVP] if reported at fair value) • Land held for sale in the normal course of business, including trading land (Investment Property, Gross (ADIC), or as Fair Value of Investment Property [AFVP] if reported at fair value) • Land held for sale outside the normal course of business, including property for sale after being used by the company, part of the company’s asset disposal group (Long Term Assets of Discontinued Operations [ADOA]) • Non-renewable natural resources in coal and oil companies (mineral and fossil fuel deposits – Mining /Exploration Specific Assets, Gross [AMIC]) • Natural resources in coal and oil companies (Natural Resources/Biological Assets, Gross [ABAC]) • Proven or unproven properties in oil and other mining companies (Natural Resources/Biological Assets, Gross [ABAC]) • Natural gas, crude oil or mining exploration sites, drilling wells and mines (Mining /Exploration Specific Assets, Gross [AMIC]) • Power plant/distribution establishments in utility companies (Utility Plant, Gross [AUTP]) • Property reported within tangible assets, leased out under operating lease contracts, generating rental income (Assets Leased Out under Operating Lease, Gross [ABLC]) • Land at cost held for investment, capital appreciation or rental purposes (Investment Property, Gross [ADIC])

i.d: Private Company. Land & Improvements, Net [SNLI] represents net book value (after depreciation) of land and improvements in land and also land not either freehold or leasehold land. Applicable to Industrial companies. Land & Improvements, Net [SNLI] includes the net book value of: • Land • Land improvements • Land portion of timberland • Logging roads for cutting timber • Land use rights when reported within property, plant and equipment breakout Land & Improvements, Net [SNLI] excludes the net book value of: • Land and buildings (Land and Buildings, Net [ALSN]) • Logging roads for cutting timber (Land and Buildings, Net [ALSN])

i.d: Private Company. Legal, Statutory & Appropriated Reserves [QLGR] represents appropriation of profit in some countries based on existing laws or regulations set for a particular company or industry.The legal reserve is not generally distributable except on winding up and its purpose is to protect the interests of creditors. The reserve may be either by national law, accounting regulations or by the company's own internal constitution. Applicable to all industries. Legal, Statutory & Appropriated Reserves [QLGR] includes: • Legal Reserves • Special Reserves • Statutory Reserve • Reserve under Banking Act/Reconstruction Act • Investment Allowance Reserve under income tax ACT • Statutory and free Reserve

Customer Liabilities on Acceptances and Custody Securities [STLBE] represents the value of all current & non-current liabilities including short term and long term debts (Total Liabilities [STLB]) less the sum of contingent assets that result from transactions mediated by a bank on behalf of customer (Customer Liabilities on Acceptances (Assets) [VCAC]) and securities held by a company as the collateral for repurchase contracts, securities lending and other collateralized agreements (Securities Held under Collateral [SHUC]).

i.d: Private Company. Loans & Receivables, Net - Current [SCLR] represents a combination of total loans, receivables and other receivables after Provision for Doubtful Accounts. Applicable to Industrial, Property, Investment and Other Financial industries Loans & Receivables, Net - Current [SCLR] includes: • Receivables due after 1 Year Included within Current Receivables [ALRC] • Total receivables • Income tax receivables • Research and development tax rebate • Tax refunds • Taxes recoverable • Accrued income taxes • Negative Income Tax Receivable – Net/Gross [ANTX]

i.d: Private Company. Loans, Net/Gross [SLNS] represents loans receivables, net, and interest-earning receivables from the sales of goods, products and services, after the provisions for doubtful loans and notes. This item is applicable to differentiated balance sheet. Applicable to all industries. Loans, Net/Gross [SLNS] includes: • Loan Receivable • Short term loan receivable • Notes receivables • Trade notes receivable • Interest-earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries • Loan to employees (if interest-earning) • Loan to stock holder (if interest-earning) • Any other interest-earning receivables • Unearned interest income on loans • Current portion of financial lease receivables, after the provision for loan losses • Provision for doubtful short-term loans and receivables from loans • Provision for doubtful receivables earning interest (promissory notes receivable) • Current portion of the provision for doubtful financial lease receivables • Loans, loan receivables and notes receivable before provisions for doubtful loans/notes (Loan/Notes Receivables, Gross [ALRF]) • Current portion of financial lease receivables, before the provision for loan losses (Loan/Notes Receivables, Gross [ALRF]) • Unearned interest income on loans, for industrial and property companies (Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ACLR]) Loans, Net/Gross [SLNS] excludes: • Non-interest earning trade receivables, net (Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR]) • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries (Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR] if clearly described as trade receivables, or as Other Receivables, Net [AORC] if reported outside trade receivables) • Due from related parties (Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR] if clearly described as trade receivables, or as Other Receivables, Net [AORC] if reported outside trade receivables) • Receivables from employees, officers, directors, or shareholders (Other Receivables, Net [AORC]) • Provision for non-interest earning trade receivables (Provision for Doubtful Trade Accounts [APDA]) • Provision for receivables other than trade receivables (Provision for Doubtful Accounts [APDB]) • Provision for combined trade and other receivables (Provision for Doubtful Accounts [APDB])

i.d: Private Company. Loans & Notes Receivables, Net [ACLR] represents loan receivables and interest-earning receivables from the sales of goods, products and services, after the provisions for doubtful loans and notes. Notes receivable are frequently used to settle overdue trade receivable balances. Applicable to Industrial, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. Loans & Notes Receivables, Net [ACLR] includes: • Loan Receivable • Short term loan receivable • Notes receivables • Trade notes receivable • Interest-earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries • Loan to employees (if interest-earning) • Loan to stock holder (if interest-earning) • Any other interest-earning receivables • Unearned interest income on loans • Current portion of financial lease receivables, after the provision for loan losses Loans & Notes Receivables, Net [ACLR] excludes: • Loans, loan receivables and notes receivable before provisions for doubtful loans/notes (Loan/Notes Receivables, Gross [ALRF]) • Current portion of financial lease receivables, before the provision for loan losses (Loan/Notes Receivables, Gross [ALRF]) • Non-interest earning trade receivables, net (Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR]) • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries (Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR] if clearly described as trade receivables, or as Other Receivables, Net [AORC] if reported outside trade receivables) • Due from related parties (Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR] if clearly described as trade receivables, or as Other Receivables, Net [AORC] if reported outside trade receivables) • Receivables from employees, officers, directors, or shareholders (Other Receivables, Net [AORC])

Applicable to all industries. LT Debt excl. Capitalized Leases [LLTD] includes: • Debt items (excluding capitalized leases) • Discounts and amortized costs LT Debt excl. Capitalized Leases [LLTD] excludes: • Total capital leases including current portion which cannot be separated [LCLT]

LT Debt excl. Capitalized Leases – Financial Sector [LLTDF] includes: • Debt items (excluding capitalized leases) applicable to financial sector [LDXTF] • Discounts and amortized costs LT Debt excl. Capitalized Leases [LLTD] excludes: • Total capital leases including current portion which cannot be separated [LCLTF]

i.d: Private Company. LT Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN] represents long-term claims held against customers for goods sold or services rendered, after the provision for doubtful long-term trade receivables. Applicable to Industrial and Property companies. LT Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN] includes: • Long-term trade receivables (net of provision for doubtful accounts) • Long-term accounts receivable (net of provision for doubtful accounts) • Non-interest earning factored/factoring receivables • Rent receivable in real estate operations companies (net of provision for doubtful accounts) • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries, if clearly described as trade receivables or reported within trade receivables • Advisory fees receivable in investment service companies • Royalty/franchise fees receivable in franchising businesses • Long-term unbilled receivables LT Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN] excludes: • Receivables from employees, officers, directors (Other Non-Current Receivables, Net [ALON]) • Long-term receivables from financial/capitalized lease contracts (Long Term Finance Lease Receivables, Net [ALFL]) • Long-term loans, notes receivable and interest-earning receivables other than arising from financial leases (Loans/Notes Receivables, Gross - Non Current [ALNG]) • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries, if reported outside trade receivables (Other Non-current Receivables, Net [ALOG]) • Receivables from stockholders (Other Non-current Receivables, Net [ALOG]) •Islamic Receivables, NonCurrent (ISRL)

i.d: Private Company. LT Accrued Expenses [LLAE] represents expenses accrued that will be paid in more than one year or after the end of the company’s inventory operating cycle. This applies to differentiated balance sheet. Applicable to Industrial, Insurance, Bank and Property companies. LT Accrued Expenses [LLAE] includes: • Long-term accrued expenses such as wages/salaries accrued/payable, accrued compensation to employees, social security obligations • Other accrued expenses reported within long-term liabilities LT Accrued Expenses [LLAE] excludes: • Trade accounts payable to suppliers or other payables (LT Trade Payables [LLTP]) • Accrued pension, post-retirement and healthcare benefits (Non-Current Post Employment Benefits - Pensions & Other [LPEN]) • Interest accrued/payable (Interest Payable - Short Term Debt [LSIP]) • Deferred income taxes payable (Deferred Taxation [LBDT], Deferred Tax (Debit) - Liability [LDTF], Deferred Tax Credit - Liability [LDTE], Net Deferred Tax Liability [LDTN]) • Long-term debt, bills of exchange and notes payable (LT Debt excl. Capitalized Leases [LLTD])

i.l: LT Finance Leases & Hire Purchase Agreements (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. LT Finance Leases & Hire Purchase Agreements [LCLO] represents obligations outstanding under finance lease and hire purchase agreement and reported as Long-Term. LCLO is collected when the current portion of capital lease cannot be broken out. Capitalized Lease Obligations imply ownership. The leaseholder acquires essentially all the economic benefits as well as the risks of the leased property. In order to qualify as a capital lease it must meet the following criteria: 1. The lease transfers ownership to the lessee at the end of the lease term. 2. A bargain price option should exist. 3. The lease term is for 75% or more of the life of the property. 4. The present value equals or exceeds the fair market value of the property by 90%. Applicable to all industries. LT Finance Leases & Hire Purchase Agreements [LCLO] includes: • Industrial Revenue Bonds which are asset backed (Long Term) • Finance Leases (Long Term) • Hire Purchase Agreement (Long Term) LT Finance Leases & Hire Purchase Agreements [LCLO] excludes • Current Portion of LT Debt/Capital Leases – [LCLD] • Capitalized Lease Obligation (Long Term + Short Term) [LCLT]

This FCC is used to collected current portion of capital lease when the same cannot be broken out. Capitalized Lease Obligations imply ownership. The leaseholder acquires essentially all the economic benefits as well as the risks of the leased property. In order to qualify as a capital lease it must meet the following criteria: 1. The lease transfers ownership to the lessee at the end of the lease term. 2. A bargain price option should exist. 3. The lease term is for 75% or more of the life of the property. 4. The present value equals or exceeds the fair market value of the property by 90%. Applicable to all industries. LT Finance Leases & Hire Purchase Agreements – Financial Sector [LCLOF] includes: • Industrial Revenue Bonds which are asset backed (Long Term) • Finance Leases (Long Term) • Hire Purchase Agreement (Long Term) LT Finance Leases & Hire Purchase Agreements – Financial Sector [LCLOF] excludes: • Current Portion of Long Term Debt/Capital Leases applicable to conglomerates – [LCLDF] • Capital lease (Long Term + Short Term) applicable to conglomerates [LCLTF]

LT Trade Payables [LLTP] represents non-current portion of amounts payable/owed to creditors or suppliers for materials and merchandise acquired or for services provided within the normal operations of the business. This applies to differentiated balance sheet. Applicable to Industrial and Property companies. LT Trade Payables [LLTP] includes: • Trade creditors for the goods and services provided • Accounts payable to joint ventures, partnerships • Bills Payable reported as part of Trade/Accounts Payable • Long-term payables to/due to related parties, affiliates and associates LT Trade Payables [LLTP]] excludes: • Trade payables combined with accrued expenses (Payable/Accrued [LPBA]) • Deferred income taxes payable (Deferred Taxation [LBDT], Deferred Tax (Debit) - Liability [LDTF], Deferred Tax Credit - Liability [LDTE], Net Deferred Tax Liability [LDTN]) • Interest accrued/payable (Interest Payable - Short Term Debt [LSIP]) • Long-term accrued expenses such as wages/salaries accrued/payable, accrued compensation to employees and accrued rent (LT Accrued Expenses [LLAE]) • Long-term debt, bills of exchange and notes payable (LT Debt excl. i.l: Minority Interest/Noncontrol Interest - no b/d, Total (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. Minority Interests/Non-Controlling Interests - No Breakdown - Total [LMIN] refers to minority interest reported within liabilities and in the shareholders’ equity. Applicable to all industries Minority/non-controlling interest is an accumulated interest for minority shareholders in subsidiaries that are less than 100 percent owned by the reporting parent company. The net worth of a subsidiary is assumed to be proportionally owned by parent company and other minority shareholders according to their respective ownership percentage. Applicable to all industries. Minority Interests/Non-Controlling Interests - No Breakdown - Total [LMIN] includes: • A combination of minority interests reported within liabilities and in the shareholders’ equity (Minority Interests/Non-Controlling Interests - Total - no b/d [LMIN]) Minority Interests/Non-Controlling Interests - No Breakdown - Total [LMIN] excludes: • Minority interests reported in the liability section (Non-Equity Minority Interest [LNMI]) • Minority interests reported in the equity section (Equity Minority Interest/Equity Non-Controlling Interests (QMIN)

i.d: Private Company. Mortgage Servicing Rights, Gross [SMRG] represents the gross value of the right to service a portfolio of loans, purchased from the loan’s originator, before accumulated amortization and impairment. The right results in the obligation to collect and transfer loan payments to the loan originator, pay taxes and insurance premiums from escrow accounts, oversee the foreclosure process, as well as to perform other administrative duties, in exchange for a pre-determined fee. Applicable to Banks. Mortgage Servicing Rights, Gross [SMRG] excludes: • Mortgage Servicing Rights, Net [AMRN] • Mortgage Servicing Rights, Amortization [AMRA]

i.d: Private Company. Net Claims Against Market Value [SCLAMV] represents the difference between the sum of total debt (both short term and long term), preferred shareholders equity and the value of cash and short term investments.

i.d: Private Company. Net Operating Assets [SNOPA] represents the sum of total shareholders’ equity including minority interest, the total value of all borrowings reported by the company and the value of non-controlling interests reported within liabilities. For banks, insurance and other financial companies the result is diminished by subtracting the total value of cash on hand and short term deposits due from other banks (Cash & ST Investments--Total [SCSTI]). Applicable to all industries. Net Operating Assets [SNOPA] includes: • Total Shareholder's Equity incl. Minority Interest & Hybrid Debt [STLE] • Total Debt [SLSD] • Non-Equity Minority Interest [SNMI]

Non-Cash Working Capital [SNCWC] represents the value of all current assets (Total Current Assets [STCA]) less the value of all current liabilities (Current Liabilities - Total [SCLT])and less the value of cash and short term investments (Cash & ST Investments [SCSI]). Applicable to all industries.

Non-Contributed Equity (Reserves & Retained Earnings) [SRES] includes: • Legal, Statutory, Appropriated Reserves [QLGR] • Retained Earnings [QRED] • Distributions in excess of Earnings [QDXE] • General reserves [QGRE] • Untaxed/Special Reserves [SUTR] • Other Reserves/Equity [QOTE] • Notes receivable in Equity [QNRE] • Loans - Other Reserve/Equity [QLOA] • Negative Consolidation Differences/Negative Goodwill/Cumulative Amount Written-off against Reserves [QGWR] • Grants [QGRA] • Stock Options under ESOP [QEDS] • Convertible Debt in Equity [QCVD] • Cumulative Goodwill Written Off [QCGW] Accumulated Comprehensive Income - Total [SACI]

i.d: Private Company. Non-Controlling Interest Included within Equity [SMNE] represents a combination of non-controlling/minority interests reported within liabilities and in the shareholders’ equity. Minority/non-controlling interest is an accumulated interest for minority shareholders in subsidiaries that are less than 100 percent owned by the reporting parent company. The net worth of a subsidiary is assumed to be proportionally owned by parent company and other minority shareholders according to their respective ownership percentage. Applicable to all industries. Non-Controlling Interest Included within Equity [SMNE] includes: • A combination of minority interests reported within liabilities and in the shareholders’ equity (LMIN) Non-Controlling Interest included within Equity [SMNE] excludes: • Minority interests reported in the liability section (LNMI) • Minority interests reported in the equity section (QMIN)

i.d: Private Company. Non-Convertible Debt, Non-Current [LNCD] represents debt or interest bearing financial obligations where the current portion and long term portion of Debt cannot be separated. This debt won’t be converted into the issuing company’s stock. Applicable to all industries. Non-Convertible Debt, Non-Current [LNCD] includes: • Debt items (excluding capitalized leases) • Discounts & amortized costs Non-Convertible Debt, Non-Current [LNCD] excludes: • Total capital leases including current portion which cannot be separated. (LCLT-Total Capitalized Lease Obligations - LT & ST) • Current maturities (Current Portion of LT Debt/Capital Leases [LCLD]) • Capital leases excluding current portion (LT Finance Leases & Hire Purchase Agreements [LCLO])

i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Accrued Expenses [SLAE] represents expenses accrued that will be paid in more than one year or after the end of the company’s inventory operating cycle. This applies to differentiated balance sheet. Applicable to Industrial, Insurance, Bank and Property companies. Non-Current Accrued Expenses [SLAE] includes: • Long-term accrued expenses such as wages/salaries accrued/payable, accrued compensation to employees, social security obligations • Other accrued expenses reported within long-term liabilities Non-Current Accrued Expenses [SLAE] excludes: • Trade accounts payable to suppliers or other payables (LT Trade Payables [LLTP]) • Accrued pension, post-retirement and healthcare benefits (Non-current Postemployment Benefits - Pensions and Other [LPEN]) • Interest accrued/payable (Interest Payable - ST debt [LSIP]) • Deferred income taxes payable (Deferred Taxation [LBDT], Deferred Tax (Debit) - Liability [LDTF], Deferred Tax Credit - Liability [LDTE], Net Deferred Tax Liability [LDTN]) • Long-term debt, bills of exchange and notes payable (LT Debt excl. Capitalized Leases [LLTD])

i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Capitalized Lease Obligations [SLCL] represents obligations outstanding under finance lease and hire purchase agreement and reported as Long-Term. Capitalized Lease Obligations imply ownership. The leaseholder acquires essentially all the economic benefits as well as the risks of the leased property. In order to qualify as a capital lease it must meet the following criteria: 1. The lease transfers ownership to the lessee at the end of the lease term. 2. A bargain price option should exist. 3. The lease term is for 75% or more of the life of the property. 4. The present value equals or exceeds the fair market value of the property by 90% Applicable to all industries. Non-Current Capitalized Lease Obligations [SLCL] includes: • Industrial Revenue Bonds which are asset backed (Long Term) • Finance Leases (Long Term) • Hire Purchase Agreement (Long Term) • Capitalized Lease Obligation (Long Term + Short Term) [LCLT] Non-Current Capitalized Lease Obligations [SLCL] excludes • Current Portion of LT Debt/Capital Leases – [LCLD]

i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Customer Advances [SCAL] refers to advances received from customers for goods or services expected to be delivered within more than one year, or in a period longer than the company’s inventory operating cycle. Applicable to Industrial and Other Financial companies. Non-Current Customer Advances [SCAL] includes: • Advance payments received from customers, shareholders • Non-current unearned contract billings Non-Current Customer Advances [SCAL] excludes: • Advance billings to customers in excess of projects completed (Billings in Excess of Cost - Current [LBEX] • Unearned revenues for goods and services that are not accounted for on a long-term contract basis (Non-Current Deferred Income [LDIL])

Capitalized Leases [SDXL] includes: • Total convertible debt excluding current portion • Total non-convertible debt excluding current portion Non-Current Debt excl. Capitalized Leases [SDXL] excludes: • Current maturities of convertible debt (Current Portion of LT Debt/Capital Leases [LCLD]) • Total Convertible debt where current portion cannot be separated (Convertible Debt - Long Term and Short Term [LCDT]

Non-Current Deferred Charges [SNDC] represents the net value of deferred costs including the fuel cost which are not recognized as a cost during the period in which it is incurred. Non-Current Deferred Charges [SNDC] is a sum of: • Non-Current Deferred Fuel Costs [ALDF] • Deferred Costs, Net [ADFN] • Deferred Cost, Gross [ADFG] • Accumulated Amortization & Impairment - Deferred Costs [ADFA]

i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Deferred Income Tax [SDTA] represents the total value of net long-term deferred taxes disclosed on the asset side, i.e. long-term deferred tax credits (assets) offset with long-term deferred tax debits (liabilities). It includes also the short term portion of Deferred Income Tax included in long term assets. This item is applicable to differentiated balance sheet. Applicable to all industries. Non-Current Deferred Income Tax [SDTA] includes: • Deferred Foreign Income Taxes • Short term portion of future tax benefits (Austria) • Long-term deferred tax credits (liabilities), decreasing the value of deferred taxes receivable or increasing tax liabilities, reported in an asset footnote • Deferred tax credits (liabilities) reported in an asset footnote, representing a sum of current and non-current assets – collected in the non-differentiated balance sheet format only • Long-term deferred tax debits (assets), increasing the value of deferred taxes receivable and decreasing tax liabilities • Deferred tax debits (assets) that represent a sum of current and non-current assets – collected in the non-differentiated balance sheet format only • Long-term net deferred tax assets, i.e. long-term deferred tax debits (assets) offset with long-term deferred tax credits (liabilities) • Net deferred taxes that represent a sum of current and non-current assets – collected in the non-differentiated balance sheet format only Non-Current Deferred Income Tax [SDTA] excludes: • Current National/Foreign Income Taxes (Current Tax - Foreign [VCTF]) • Deferred State & Local Income Taxes (Deferred Tax – Local [VDTL]) • Deferred Federal/Domestic Income Taxes (Deferred Tax - Domestic [VDTD]) • Deferred Income Tax - Current Asset (reported under current assets section) (Deferred Income Tax - Current Asset [ADTC])

i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Investments [SILT] represents total non-current investment including non-current financial assets and investment property. Applicable to Industrial and Property companies. Non-Current Investments [SILT] includes: • Total Investments – Long term • Financial assets • A combination of loans, investments, derivatives and other financial assets • Net book value of investment property, even if reported in the table of tangible assets, in the U.S. and other markets • Net book value of commercial real estate earning rental income • Fair value of investment properties if reported on face of balance sheet. Non-Current Investments [SILT] excludes: • Long-term derivatives held for hedging (risk management) purposes (Non-current Derivative Financial Instruments - Hedging [ANDH]). • Non-current derivatives that haven't been described as either hedging or speculative – treated as hedging for all industrial and property companies (Non-Current Derivative Financial Instruments - Hedging [ANDH]) • Long-term investments held for sale or to maturity (Long Term Investments (Held for Sale / Held to Maturity) [ALTI]) • Short-term trading investments and other current investment assets (ST Investments [ASTI]) • Investments in non-consolidated subsidiaries, associates, affiliates, joint ventures, equity in affiliates (Investments in Associates, Joint Ventures and Unconsolidated Subsidiaries [AEQI]) • Total as reported investments (Non-Current Investments - Total [XLIU]) • Long-term derivatives held for hedging (risk management) purposes (Non-Current Derivative Financial Instruments - Hedging [ANDH]) • Non-current derivatives that haven't been described as either hedging or speculative – treated as hedging for all industrial and property companies (Non-Current Derivative Financial Instruments - Hedging [ANDH]) • Long-term investments held for sale or to maturity (Long-Term Investments (Held for Sale/Held to Maturity) [ALTI]) • Short-term trading investments and other current investment assets (ST Investments [ASTI]) • Investments in non-consolidated subsidiaries, associates, affiliates, joint ventures, equity in affiliates (Investments in Associates, Joint Ventures and Unconsolidated Subsidiaries [AEQI]) • Buildings held for own use in the table of tangible assets (Buildings, Net [APBN]) • Property under construction or development, intended for sale in the ordinary course of business (Inventories - Non-Current [ANIN]) • Property constructed/developed on behalf of third parties as part of a construction contract (Other Tangible Fixed Assets, Net [AOPN]) • Fair value of investment property if reported in notes (Fair Value of Investment Property [AFVP])

i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Investments Held for Sale & Held to Maturity [SLTI] represents long-term investments held for sale or to maturity. It includes the fair value of long-term derivative instruments used for speculative/trading purposes. Examples of derivatives include future or forward contracts, call or put options, swaps etc. Speculative derivative instruments are investments bought in the expectation of their future value increase. Applicable to all industries. Non-Current Investments Held for Sale & Held to Maturity [SLTI] includes: • Other long-term investments Non-Current Investments Held for Sale & Held to Maturity [SLTI] excludes: • Short-term trading investments and other current investment assets • Investment properties (AVPN, AFVP) • Investments in non-consolidated subsidiaries, associates, affiliates, joint ventures, equity in affiliates (AEQI) • Non-Current marketable securities (AMSL) • Long-term derivative assets held for speculative/trading/investment purposes (ALDS) • Total non-current investments (XLIU) • Non-Current Financial Assets (AFAN) • Non-current derivatives that haven't been described as either hedging or speculative – treated as hedging for all commercial/industrial companies (ANDH)
