i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Loans, Net/Gross [SLNG] represents long-term loans, notes receivable and other interest-earning non-current receivables, both before and after the provision for doubtful loans/note receivables. This refers to loan receivables and interest-earning receivables from the sales of goods, products and services, after the provisions for doubtful loans and notes. Notes receivable are frequently used to settle overdue trade receivable balances. Applicable to Industrial, Property and Investment companies. Non-Current Loans, Net/Gross [SLNG] includes: • Long-term loans receivable • Long-term notes receivable • Long-term trade notes receivable • Long-term interest-earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and unconsolidated subsidiaries • Long-term loan to employees (if interest-earning) • Long-term loan to stockholders (if interest-earning) • Any other interest-earning receivables • Long-term portion of unearned interest income on loans and notes receivable Non-Current Loans, Net/Gross [SLNG] excludes: • Long-term net receivables from financial/capitalized lease contracts (Long Term Finance Lease Receivables, Net [ALFL]) • Long-term, non-interest earning trade or other receivables, net (Long Term Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN]) • Long-term, non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and unconsolidated subsidiaries (Long Term Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN] if clearly described as trade receivables, or as Other Receivables, Net [AORC] if reported outside trade receivables) • Long-term due from related parties (Long Term Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN] if clearly described as trade receivables, or as Other Receivables, Net [AORC] if reported outside trade receivables) • Long-term receivables from employees, officers, directors, or shareholders (Other Non-urrent Receivables, Net [ALON])

i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ALNN] represents long-term loans, notes receivable and other interest-earning non-current receivables, after the provision for doubtful loans/note receivables. This refers to loan receivables and interest-earning receivables from the sales of goods, products and services, after the provisions for doubtful loans and notes. Notes receivable are frequently used to settle overdue trade receivable balances. Applicable to Industrial, Property and Investment companies. Non-Current Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ALNN] includes: • Long-term loans receivable • Long-term notes receivable • Long-term trade notes receivable • Long-term interest-earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and unconsolidated subsidiaries • Long-term loan to employees (if interest-earning) • Long-term loan to stockholders (if interest-earning) • Any other interest-earning receivables • Long-term portion of unearned interest income on loans and notes receivable Non-Current Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ALNN] excludes: • Long-term net loans, loan receivables and notes receivable before provisions for doubtful loans/notes (Loans/Notes Receivables, Gross - Non Current [ALNG]) • Long-term net receivables from financial/capitalized lease contracts (Long Term Finance Lease Receivables, Net [ALFL]) • Long-term, non-interest earning trade or other receivables, net (LT Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN]) • Long-term, non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and unconsolidated subsidiaries (LT Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN] if clearly described as trade receivables, or as Other Receivables, Net [AORC] if reported outside trade receivables) • Long-term due from related parties (LT Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN] if clearly described as trade receivables, or as Other Receivables, Net [AORC] if reported outside trade receivables) • Long-term receivables from employees, officers, directors, or shareholders (Other Non-urrent Receivables, Net [ALON])

i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Other Assets – Total [SOAS] refers to the other long term assets. Includes prepaid expenses disclosed outside current assets and due after one year, non-current Inventories, deposits, deferred income tax, deferred charges and pension benefits. Applicable to all industries. Non-Current Other Assets – Total [SOAS] includes: • Refundable customer deposits • Cash in escrow accounts. • Regulatory assets reported by U.S. and Canadian companies • Deferred fuel costs if reported within the regulatory breakdown should be left within the regulatory assets • Treasury stock and shares held by employee share trusts when reported as part of total assets (rather than as a deduction from shareholders' funds) • ESOT/Plan in Own Equity Shares [AEST] • Other Long Term Assets [AOLA] • Interim Dividend [AIDT] • Accumulated deficit • Accumulated losses • Properties held for sale (non-current finished goods) • Other inventories reported in the non current section outside current assets • Prepaid expenses reported under non current section Non-Current Other Assets – Total [SOAS] excludes: • Deferred fuel costs if reported separately (Non-Current Deferred Fuel Costs [ALDF]) • Own shares reported as current assets • Time deposit (ST Investments [ASTI]) • Segregated Cash Deposits (Segregated Cash Deposits [ACCD]) • Cash deposits and Investments Segregated (Cash and Investments Segregated [ACIS]) • Other segregated deposits (Other Segregated Deposits [ACOS]) • Prepayment for pension benefits or any employment-related items such as post-retirement health benefits (Long Term Pension Assets [APBO] • Prepayments combined with accrued income and/or deferred costs (Other Deferred Charges/Prepayments [AODC])

i.l: Non-Current Post Employ Benefit, Pension & Oth (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Post Employment Benefits - Pensions & Other [LPEN] refers to provisions for future pension liabilities. Includes retirement benefits, pension reserves, healthcare plans and post-employment obligations. Applicable to all industries. Non-current Postemployment Benefits – Pensions and Other [LPEN] excludes: • Asset Retirement Obligation - Non-Current [LARE] • Long term provision for litigation (Provision for Litigation - Non-Current [LLGR]) • Non-current Restructuring provisions (Restructuring Provisions - Non-Current [LRSR]) • Provision for Environment Obligations - Non-Current [LPVE] • Other non-current provisions not specifically reported as any of the above components (Other Provisions expect Pension & Post Retirement Provisions [LRSV]) • Non-current provisions reported without any breakout (Non-Current Provisions – Total – no b/d [LNCU])

i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Provisions – Total – no b/d [LNCU] represents the sum of all non-current provisions when the provisions are not broken out into components. Applicable to Industrial, Property and Investment companies. Non-Current Provisions – Total – no b/d [LNCU] excludes: • Non-Current Post Employment Benefits - Pensions & Other [LPEN] • Asset Retirement Obligation - Non-Current [LARE] • Long term provision for litigation (Provision for Litigation - Non-Current [LLGR]) • Non-current Restructuring provisions (Restructuring Provisions - Non-Current [LRSR]) • Provision for Environment Obligations - Non-Current [LPVE] • Other non-current provisions not specifically reported as any of the above components (Other Provisions - Other Than Pension/Post-Retirement [LRSV])

i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Receivables - Other, Net/Gross [SLRO] represents any receivables other than those generated by sales of products, goods and services, loans and notes receivable, or other receivables represented by specific codes, both before and after the provision for doubtful other receivables. Applicable to Industrial, Insurance, Bank and Property companies. Non-Current Receivables - Other, Net/Gross [SLRO] includes: • Receivables from/due from employees, officers, directors, or shareholders • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries, if reported outside trade receivables • Due from related parties, if reported outside trade receivables Non-Current Receivables - Other, Net/Gross [SLRO] excludes: • Receivables from the sales of products, goods and services (Long-Term Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN]) • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries, if clearly described as trade receivables, or reported within trade receivables (Long-Term Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN]) • Long-term unbilled utility revenue (Long-Term Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN]) • Interest-earning receivables from loans issued and promissory notes receivable (Non-Current Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ALNN]) • Long-term contract receivables (Long-Term Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN]) • Credit card receivables (common for retail companies) (Long-Term Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN]) • Service contracts receivable (Long-Term Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN]) • Long-term deferred taxes (Deferred Tax Asset - Long Term [ADTA]) • Current accrued income (Other Long Term Assets – Total [XOLT] if reported on the face, or as Other Long Term Assets [AOLA] if reported in a breakout of face items) • Islamic Receivables, Non-current [ISRL] Financial lease receivables (Finance Lease Receivables, Net [ACFR]) • Loan receivables (Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ACLR]) • Income tax receivables (Income Tax Receivables - Net/Gross [AOTX]) • Trade receivables (Long-Term Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN]) • Contract receivables (Long-Term Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN])

i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Receivables & Loans [SLLR] represents the total value of any net and gross receivables other than those generated by sales of products, goods and services, loans and notes receivable, or other receivables represented by specific codes, after the provision for doubtful other receivables. This item includes long-term loans, notes receivable and other interest-earning non-current receivables, after the provision for doubtful loans/note receivables and Islamic receivables. Non-Current Receivables & Loans [SLLR] includes: • Receivables from/due from employees, officers, directors, or shareholders • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries, if reported outside trade receivables • Due from related parties, if reported outside trade receivables • Long-term loans receivable • Long-term notes receivable • Long-term trade notes receivable • Long-term interest-earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and unconsolidated subsidiaries • Long-term loan to employees (if interest-earning) • Long-term loan to stockholders (if interest-earning) • Any other interest-earning receivables • Long-term portion of unearned interest income on loans and notes receivable • Long-term loans and receivables from loans • Non-current receivables earning interest (promissory notes receivable) • Non-current trade notes receivable • Long-term, interest-earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and unconsolidated subsidiaries Non-Current Receivables & Loans [SLLR] excludes: • Receivables from the sales of products, goods and services (LT Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN]) • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries, if clearly described as trade receivables, or reported within trade receivables (LT Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN]) • Long-term unbilled utility revenue (LT Accounts/Trade Receivables, Net [ALRN]) • Interest-earning receivables from loans issued and promissory notes receivable (Non-current Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ALNN]) • Long-term contract receivables (ALRN) • Credit card receivables (common for retail companies) [ALRN] • Service contracts receivable (ALRN) • Current accrued income (classified as Other Long Term Assets – Total [XOLT] if reported on the face, or as Other Long Term Assets [AOLA] if reported in a breakout of face items)

i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Trade Accounts Payables [SLTL] represents non-current portion of amounts payable/owed to creditors or suppliers for materials and merchandise acquired or for services provided within the normal operations of the business. This applies to differentiated balance sheet. Applicable to Industrial and Property companies. Non-Current Trade Accounts Payables [SLTL] includes: • Trade creditors for the goods and services provided • Accounts payable to joint ventures, partnerships • Bills Payable reported as part of Trade/Accounts Payable • Long-term payables to/due to related parties, affiliates and associates Non-Current Trade Accounts Payables [SLTL] excludes: • Trade payables combined with accrued expenses (Payable/Accrued [LPBA]) • Deferred income taxes payable (Deferred Taxation [LBDT], Deferred Tax (Debit) - Liability [LDTF], Deferred Tax Credit - Liability [LDTE], Net Deferred Tax Liability [LDTN]) • Interest accrued/payable (Interest Payable - ST debt [LSIP]) • Long-term accrued expenses such as wages/salaries accrued/payable, accrued compensation to employees and accrued rent (LT Accrued Expenses [LLAE]) • Long-term debt, bills of exchange and notes payable (LT Debt excl. Capitalized Leases [LLTD])

i.l: Non-Current Trade Account Payable & Accr Expns (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. Non-Current Trade Accounts Payables & Accrued Expenses [SLAP] represents non-current portion of amounts payable/owed to creditors or suppliers for materials and merchandise acquired or for services provided within the normal operations of the business. It includes the expenses accrued that will be paid in more than one year or after the end of the company’s inventory operating cycle. Applicable to Industrial and Property companies. Non-Current Trade Accounts Payables & Accrued Expenses [SLAP] includes: • Trade creditors for the goods and services provided • Accounts payable to joint ventures, partnerships • Bills Payable reported as part of Trade/Accounts Payable • Long-term payables to/due to related parties, affiliates and associates • Long-term accrued expenses such as wages/salaries accrued/payable, accrued compensation to employees, social security obligations • Other accrued expenses reported within long-term liabilities Non-Current Trade Accounts Payables & Accrued Expenses [SLAP] includes excludes: • Deferred income taxes payable (Deferred Taxation [LBDT], Deferred Tax (Debit) - Liability [LDTF], Deferred Tax Credit - Liability [LDTE], Net Deferred Tax Liability [LDTN]) • Interest accrued/payable (Interest Payable - ST debt [LSIP]) • Long-term accrued expenses such as wages/salaries accrued/payable, accrued compensation to employees and accrued rent (LT Accrued Expenses [LLAE]) • Long-term debt, bills of exchange and notes payable (LT Debt excl. Capitalized Leases [LLTD]) • Accrued pension, post-retirement and healthcare benefits (Non-current Postemployment Benefits - Pensions and Other [LPEN])

Other Current Assets [SCAO] represents current assets other than current deferred income tax, current deferred costs, current restricted cash and short-term investments, cash, short-term investments, inventories, derivatives or receivables. Other Current Assets - Total [SOCA] represents current assets including those classified as current deferred income tax, current deferred costs, current restricted cash and short-term investments, cash, short-term investments, inventories, derivatives or receivables as well as all rounding adjustments in current assets section. Other Current Assets - Total [SOCA] includes • Other current assets reported in footnotes • Other current assets reported within the breakout of other current assets on the face of balance sheet • Deferred Income Tax - Current Asset (Deferred Income Tax - Current Asset [ADTC]) • Regulatory Assets – Current (Regulatory Assets – Current [ARAC] • Deferred Costs – Current (Deferred Costs - Current [ADFC] • Deferred Fuel Costs – Current (Deferred Fuel Costs – Current [ACDF] Other Current Assets - Total [SOCA] excludes: • ST Accrued Income (ST Accrued Income [AAIC] • Prepayments (Prepayments [APPY] • Prepaid Expenses and Other Current Assets (Prepaid Expenses & Other Current Assets [APYO] • Assets held for sale / assets for sale from discontinued operations (ST Assets Held for Sale/from Discontinued Operations [ADCA]

i.d: Private Company. Other Current Liabilities [SCLO] represents other current liabilities, reported in the notes or within a breakout of items from the face. Includes any payables other than income tax payable, dividend payable, interest payable which are expected to mature within one year or an operating cycle, whichever is longer. Applicable to Industrial, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. Other Current Liabilities [SCLO] includes: • Acquisition-related expenses accrued • Merger-related expenses • Integration expenses • Advances from shareholders • Dividends to minority shareholders of subsidiary • Restructuring expenses • Payables/due to employees, shareholders, officers, directors (other than loans, dividends, payroll), when reported outside of trade payables • Due to related parties when reported outside trade payables • Interest Payable - Short Term Debt [LSIP] • Short-term derivatives held for speculative or trading purposes • Short-term interest-bearing speculative/trading derivatives reported under short-term debt Other Current Liabilities [SCLO] excludes: • Payable to/due to related parties, affiliates and associates, when reported within trade payables (Accounts Payable [LAPB]) • Short-term loans, notes payable and other interest-bearing debt payables (Short Term Debt and Notes Payable [LSOD]) • Current portion of long-term loans and capitalized leases (Current Portion of LT Debt/Capital Leases [LCLD]) • Dividends and distributions payable (Dividends & Distributions Payable [LDPB]) • Payables combined with accruals (Payable/Accrued [LPBA]) Short-term derivatives held for hedging purposes (Current Derivative Liabilities - Hedging [LCDV]) • Short-term interest-bearing hedging derivatives reported under short-term debt (Current Derivative Liabilities - Hedging [LCDV]) • Short-term derivative liabilities not specified as hedging or trading/speculative, for industrial and property companies (Current Derivative Liabilities Hedging [LCDV]) • Short-term interest-bearing derivative liabilities not specified as hedging or trading/speculative, for industrial and property companies, reported within short-term debt (Current Derivative Liabilities - Hedging [LCDV]) • Short-term trading/speculative derivatives for bank, insurance, investment and other financial companies – collected under codes specific for these industries

i.d: Private Company. Own Equity Shares [AOET] represents the purchase of own shares by the company itself. Reported in historic periods. Also known as "treasury stock", this represents the company's own shares purchased and held by itself or a group entity, and reported as a fixed or non-current asset. Applicable to all industries. Own Equity Shares [AOET] includes: • Treasury stock and shares held by employee share trusts when reported as part of total assets (rather than as a deduction from shareholders' funds) Own Equity Shares [AOET] excludes: • Own shares reported as current assets

i.d: Private Company. Payables & Accrued Expenses [SPAB] represents the combined value of payables and accrued expenses Payables & Accrued Expenses [SPAB] includes: • Accounts payable and accrued expenses • Accrued expenses, when not included in more specific categories such as accrued payroll, dividends, interest payable, and income tax payable • Payroll taxes • Sales Tax • Taxes other than income taxes • Property taxes • Excise taxes • General & Service taxes • Ad Valorem • Commission (not relating to employees or when the company is silent) • Long-term accrued expenses such as wages/salaries accrued/payable, accrued compensation to employees, social security obligations • Other accrued expenses reported within long-term liabilities • Accrued payroll • Payroll taxes payable • Accrued compensation expenses • Accrued profit sharing • Commission (relating to employees) • Accrued bonus • Vacation pay • Social security obligations • Trade creditors for the goods and services provided • Accounts payable to joint ventures, partnerships • Bills Payable reported as part of Trade/Accounts Payable • Payable to/due to related parties, affiliates and associates, when reported within trade payables Payables & Accrued Expenses [SPAB] excludes: • Accrued expenses such as interest accrued/payable, when delineated separately (Interest Payable - Short Term Debt [LSIP]) • Accrued expenses such as wages/salaries accrued/payable, accrued compensation to employees (Accrued Payroll [LCAP]) • Accrued/expenses payable towards income taxes (Income Taxes Payable [LTXP]) • Dividends payable (common or preferred) (Dividends & Distributions Payable [LDPB]) • Any other accrued expenses towards rent or other expenses etc (Accrued Expenses [LCAE]) • Notes/mortgage loans payable (ST Debt and Notes Payable [LSOD]) • Payables towards Income taxes (Income Taxes Payable [LTXP]) • Payables towards dividends (common or preferred) (Dividends & Distributions Payable [LDPB]) • Expenses such as interest accrued/payable (Interest Payable-ST debt [LSIP]) • Accrued expenses such as wages/salaries accrued/payable, accrued compensation to employees (Accrued Payroll [LCAP]) • Bills of exchange and notes payable (ST Debt & Notes Payable [LSOD]) • Short-term debt payable (ST Debt & Notes Payable [LSOD] • Payable to/due to related parties, affiliates and associates, when not reported within trade payables (LOPB)

i.d: Private Company. Permanent Investments [SINVP] represents total non-current investment including non-current financial assets, investment property, investment in associated, affiliated and other companies accounted for by the equity method. Applicable to all industries. Permanent Investments [SINVP] includes: • Total Investments – Long term • Financial assets • A combination of loans, investments, derivatives and other financial assets • Net book value of investment property, even if reported in the table of tangible assets, in the U.S. and other markets • Net book value of commercial real estate earning rental income • Fair value of investment properties if reported on face of balance sheet. • Equity in affiliates/associates • Investments in affiliated/associated companies • Joint ventures • Investments in unconsolidated subsidiaries Permanent Investments [SINVP] excludes: • Long-term derivatives held for hedging (risk management) purposes (Non-current Derivative Financial Instruments - Hedging [ANDH]). • Non-current derivatives that haven't been described as either hedging or speculative – treated as hedging for all industrial and property companies (Non-Current Derivative Financial Instruments - Hedging [ANDH]) • Short-term trading investments and other current investment assets (ST Investments [ASTI]) • Long-term derivatives held for hedging (risk management) purposes (Non-Current Derivative Financial Instruments - Hedging [ANDH]) • Non-current derivatives that haven't been described as either hedging or speculative – treated as hedging for all industrial and property companies (Non-Current Derivative Financial Instruments - Hedging [ANDH]) • Short-term trading investments and other current investment assets (ST Investments [ASTI]) • Buildings held for own use in the table of tangible assets (Buildings, Net [APBN]) • Property under construction or development, intended for sale in the ordinary course of business (Inventories - Non-Current [ANIN]) • Property constructed/developed on behalf of third parties as part of a construction contract (Other Tangible Fixed Assets, Net [AOPN]) • Fair value of investment property if reported in notes (Fair Value of Investment Property [AFVP]) • Amounts due from associates, affiliates, joint ventures, unconsolidated subsidiaries and other related companies, clearly described as trade receivables or reported within trade receivables (Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR]) • Amounts due from associates, affiliates, joint ventures and other related/group companies, reported outside trade receivables (Other Receivables, Net [AORC]) • Loans to associated companies (Non-current Loans/Notes Receivables, Net [ALNN]) • Goodwill on acquisition of associated companies (Goodwill, Net [AGWN])

i.d: Private Company. Plant, Machinery & Equipment, Gross [SMEC] represents gross book value (before depreciation and impairment) of plant, machinery and other equipment. It includes machines and machine parts needed by the company to produce its products. Applicable to all industries. Plant, Machinery & Equipment, Gross [SMEC] includes: • Plant • Factory equipment • Machinery and machine parts needed by the company to produce its products, if reported within tangible assets • Mining facilities (equipment used for mining) • Oil and natural gas exploration equipment in oil and gas companies • Tools and Parts • Foreign currency transaction Plant, Machinery & Equipment, Gross [SMEC] excludes: • Software (acquired/capitalized) (Computer Software & Equipment, gross [ASCS] when reported under PPE breakup) • Transportation equipment, if reported separately (Transportation Equipment, Gross [ATPC]) • Machinery/equipment capitalized under finance lease (PPE under Capital Lease, Gross [ACLC]) • Furniture & fixtures/fittings (Other Tangible Fixed Assets, Gross [AOPC]) • Delivery equipment, office equipment (Other Tangible Fixed Assets, Gross [AOPC]) • Rental assets/assets for rent/assets leased out under operating lease (Assets Leased Out under Operating Lease, Gross [ABLC])

i.d: Private Company. Plant, Machinery & Equipment, Net [SMEN] represents the net book value (after depreciation and impairment) of all types of plant, machinery and equipment. It includes net book value of transportation equipment and computer equipment and software. Applicable to all industries. Plant, Machinery & Equipment, Net [SMEN] includes: • Fleet • Cars • Motor vehicles • Airplanes • Ships • IT equipment • Computers/Hardware • Software • Plant • Factory equipment • Machines and machine parts needed by the company to produce its products, if reported within tangible assets • Mining equipment • Oil and natural gas exploration equipment in oil and gas companies • Tools and parts. Plant, Machinery & Equipment, Net [SMEN] excludes: • Net book value of transport equipment held under capital lease and hire-purchase contracts (Property, Plant and Equipment Under Capital Lease, Net [ACLN] • Net book value of computer software reported within intangible assets (Computer Software, Net [ACSN])

i.d: Private Company. Post Employment Benefits - Pensions & Other [SPET] refers to provisions for future pension liabilities. Includes retirement benefits, pension reserves, healthcare plans and post-employment obligations. Applicable to all industries. Post Employment Benefits - Pensions & Other [SPET] excludes: • Asset Retirement Obligation - Non-Current [LARE] • Long term provision for litigation (Provision for Litigation - Non-Current [LLGR]) • Non-current Restructuring provisions (Restructuring Provisions - Non-Current [LRSR]) • Provision for Environment Obligations - Non-Current [LPVE] • Other non-current provisions not specifically reported as any of the above components (Other Provisions expect Pension & Post Retirement Provisions [LRSV]) • Non-current provisions reported without any breakout (Non-Current Provisions – Total – no b/d [LNCU])

i.l: Property, Plant & Equip excl Asset Leased Out, Gross (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. Property, Plant & Equipment excl. Assets Leased Out, Gross [SPXC] represents the value of fixed assets other than assets leased out before depreciation and impairment. Property, Plant & Equipment excl. Assets Leased Out, Gross [SPXC] includes: • Plant • Factory equipment • Machinery and machine parts needed by the company to produce its products, if reported within tangible assets • Mining facilities (equipment used for mining) • Oil and natural gas exploration equipment in oil and gas companies • Tools and Parts • Exploration and evaluation costs capitalized, if reported within tangible assets (incurred before the technical feasibility and commercial viability of extracting a mineral resource are demonstrable) • Rights to extract minerals, if reported within tangible assets • Proven and unproven crude oil and natural gas reserves • Reserves of mineral deposits, such as metal ores, coal, copper, silver, gold • Any other non-renewable (depletable) natural resources • Foreign currency transaction • Buildings, leasehold land, transport equipment, machinery, plant and any other assets held under capital lease/financial lease/hire-purchase contracts • Fixed assets installation in progress and transit • Prepayments and advances made for purchase of fixed assets • Construction in progress of fixed assets for own use • Property held for future development in companies other than real estate or construction companies • Prepayment/deposits for aircraft acquisition in airline transportation companies • Foreign currency Property, Plant & Equipment excl. Assets Leased Out, Gross [SPXC] excludes: • Mining/extraction rights and capitalized exploration/evaluation costs reported within intangible assets (Other Intangibles, Gross [AOIG]) • Land portion of timberland (Land & Improvements, Gross [ALIC]) • Logging roads for cutting timber (Land & Improvements, Gross [ALIC]) • Freehold land (Land & Improvements - Gross [ALIC]) • Buildings and premises occupied based on ownership rights, rather than financial lease agreements (Buildings, Gross [APBC]) • Own transport equipment (Transportation Equipment, Gross [ATPC]) • Own IT equipment, hardware and software, if reported within tangible assets (Computer Software & Equipment, Gross [ASCS])

i.l: Property, Plant & Equip excl Assets Leased Out, Net (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. Property, Plant & Equipment excl. Assets Leased Out, Net [SPXE] represent the net value of all tangible fixed assets excluding assets leased out. Property, Plant & Equipment excl. Assets Leased Out, Net [SPXE] includes: • Fleet • Cars • Motor vehicles • Airplanes • Ships • IT equipment • Computers/Hardware • Software • Plant • Factory equipment • Machines and machine parts needed by the company to produce its products, if reported within tangible assets • Mining equipment • Oil and natural gas exploration equipment in oil and gas companies • Tools and parts. • Land and building • Accumulated depreciation • Accumulated depletion • Accumulated amortization • Depreciation on leasehold improvements • Amortization of Property, Plant & Equipment leased under capitalized lease obligations • Excess depreciation (for Non-U.S. corporations) • Impairment of Property, Plant & Equipment Property, Plant & Equipment excl. Assets Leased Out, Net [SPXE] excludes: • Net book value of transport equipment held under capital lease and hire-purchase contracts (Property, Plant and Equipment Under Capital Lease, Net [ACLN] • Net book value of computer software reported within intangible assets (Computer Software, Net [ACSN]) • Net book value of land reported separately (Land/Improvements, Net [ALIN]) • Net book value of buildings reported separately (Buildings, Net [APBN]) • Net book value of land and/or buildings held for investment, capital appreciation or rental purposes (Investment Property, Net [AVPN]) • Foreign currency transactions (include it within its respective Gross value)

i.d: Private Company. PPE Under Capital Lease, Gross [SCLC] represents gross book value (before depreciation and impairment) of all property, plant and equipment held under capital lease and hire-purchase contracts. Applicable to all industries. PPE Under Capital Lease, Gross [SCLC] includes: • Buildings, leasehold land, transport equipment, machinery, plant and any other assets held under capital lease/financial lease/hire-purchase contracts • Foreign currency transaction PPE Under Capital Lease, Gross [SCLC] excludes: • Freehold land (Land & Improvements - Gross [ALIC]) • Buildings and premises occupied based on ownership rights, rather than financial lease agreements (Buildings, Gross [APBC]) • Own transport equipment (Transportation Equipment, Gross [ATPC]) • Own IT equipment, hardware and software, if reported within tangible assets (Computer Software & Equipment, Gross [ASCS]) • Machinery, plant and equipment not classified under more specific equipment categories (Plant, Machinery & Equipment, Gross [AMEC])

i.l: Property, Plant & Equip under Capital Leases, Net (Pvt)
i.d:
Private Company. Property, Plant and Equipment under Capital Lease, Net [SPCN] represents net book value (after depreciation and impairment) of all property, plant and equipment held under finance and capital lease and hire-purchase contracts. Applicable to Industrial companies.
Property, Plant and Equipment under Capital Leasee, Net [SPCN] includes: • Net book value of buildings, leasehold land, transport equipment, machinery, plant and any other assets held under capital lease/financial lease/hire-purchase contracts
Property, Plant and Equipment under Capital Lease, Net [SPCN] excludes the net book value of: • Freehold land (Land & Improvements, Net [ALIN]) • Buildings and premises occupied based on ownership rights, rather than financial lease agreements (Buildings, Net [APBN]) • Own transport equipment (Transportation Equipment, Net [ATPN]) • Own IT equipment, hardware and software, if reported within tangible assets (Computer Software and Equipment, Net [ASEN]) • Machinery, plant and equipment not classified under more specific equipment categories (Plant, Machinery & Equipment, Net [AMEN])

i.d:
Private Company. Preferred Shareholders' Equity [SPSE] represents the total preferred shareholders. It includes preferred stock owned by the issuing company or its consolidated subsidiaries and other preferred stock. Applicable to all industries.
Preferred Shareholders' Equity [SPSE] includes: • Treasury Stock Preferred/Repurchased Preferred Stock [STSP] • Redeemable Preferred Stock - Total [SRPS] • Non-redeemable Preferred Stocks [SNRP] • ESOP Guarantees - Preferred and Deferred Compensation [SEDP] • Contributed Preferred Equity [SCPF] • Redeemable Preference Stock - Temporary Equity [QRPM] • Preferred shareholders equity-total no b/d (QPSU)

i.d: Private Company. Prepaid Expenses [SPPT] represents the total value of goods or services that have already been purchased, but not fully consumed or used. It includes both current and non-current prepayments. This item is applicable to non-differentiated balance sheet. Prepaid Expenses [SPPT] includes: • Prepaid expenses reported under non current section • Post-retirement expenses • Prepaid expenses and accrued revenue/Prepayments and accruals • Prepaid expenses and other current asset • Advance Payment • Prepaid Lease payment • Prepaid Insurance • Prepaid Rents Foreign Exchange Loss - Long-Term Assets [AFXT] Long Term and Short Term Prepayments in Long Term Assets [ATPY] Prepayments / Accrued Income [APAI] Prepaid Expenses [SPPT] excludes: • Prepayment for pension benefits or any employment-related items such as post-retirement health benefits (Long Term Pension Assets [APBO] • Prepayments combined with accrued income and/or deferred costs (Other Deferred Charges/Prepayments [AODC]) • Prepayments for inventories (Inventories - Other [AIOT]) • Deferred Income Tax Assets (Deferred Tax – Current Assets [ADTC]) • Accrued revenue (not from main business), if separated from prepaid expenses (Short-Term Accrued Income [AAIC])

i.d: Private Company. Prepaid Expenses – Current [SPPD] represents goods or services that have already been purchased, but not fully consumed or used. Prepayments is defined as a part of current assets as such benefits are expected within one year or an operating cycle of the company, whichever is longer, from the current fiscal period end date. Prepayments may include prepaid fees, commissions, taxes, insurance expenses, prepayments to reinsurers, rents, or other expenses. Applicable to Industrial, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. Prepaid Expenses – Current [SPPD] includes: • Prepaid expenses and accrued revenue/Prepayments and accruals • Prepaid expenses and other current assets • Advance Payment • Prepaid Lease payment • Prepaid Insurance • Prepaid Rents Prepaid Expenses – Current [SPPD] excludes: • Prepayment of Inventories (Inventories – Other [AIOT]) • Deferred Income Tax Assets (Deferred Tax – Current Assets [ADTC]) • Accrued revenue (not from main business), if separated from prepaid expenses (Short-Term Accrued Income [AAIC]) • Prepayments for inventories (Inventories - Other [AIOT])

Applicable to Industrial, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. Prepaid Expenses & Other Current Assets [APYO] includes: • Prepaid expenses and accrued revenue/Prepayments and accruals • Prepaid expenses and other current assets Prepaid Expenses & Other Current Assets [APYO] excludes: • Prepayments/prepaid expenses reported as a separate item (Prepayments [APPY]) • Prepayments for inventories (Inventories - Other [AIOT])

i.d: Private Company. Prepayments [APPY] represents goods or services that have already been purchased, but not fully consumed or used. Prepayments is defined as a part of current assets as such benefits are expected within one year or an operating cycle of the company, whichever is longer, from the current fiscal period end date. Prepayments may include prepaid fees, commissions, taxes, insurance expenses, prepayments to reinsurers, rents, or other expenses. Additionally, other categories of assets may be a ‘Prepaid Asset’ depending on the company’s business. Applicable to Industrial, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. i.d: Private Company. Property, Plant & Equipment, Gross - Total [SPPC] represents total reported gross value of fixed assets before accumulated depreciation but without detailed delineation. Applicable to all industries. Property, Plant & Equipment, Gross - Total [SPPC] includes: • Land and Improvements – Gross [ALIC] • Buildings, Gross [APBC] • Leasehold Improvements, Gross [ALEC] • Land/Buildings, Gross [ALSC] • Transportation Equipment, Gross [ATPC] • Computer Software and Equipment, Gross [ASCS] • Machinery/Equipment, Gross [AMEC] • Construction in Progress, Gross [ACPC] • Property, Plant & Equipment Under Capital Lease, Gross [ACLC] • Natural Resources/Biological Assets, Gross [ABAC] • Mining /Exploration Specific Assets, Gross [AMIC] • Utility Plant, Gross [AUTP] • Other Tangible Fixed Assets, Gross [AOPC] • Assets Leased Out under Operating Lease – Gross [ABLC] Property, Plant & Equipment, Gross - Total [SPPC] excludes: • Assets of discontinued operations (Long Term Assets Held for Sale/from Discontinued Operations [ADOA])

i.d: Private Company. Provisions [SPRV] represent the value of provisions reported by the company. Applicable to all industries. Provisions [SPRV] includes: • Restructuring Provisions – Non-Current [LRSR] • Provision for Litigation – Non-Current [LLGR] • Long-term provision for the remediation of natural environment whose value is uncertain and estimated • Other Provisions - Other Than Pension/Post Retirement [LRSV] • Non-Current Provisions – Total – No Breakdown [LNCU] • Current Provisions [LCPV] • Non-Current Postemployment Benefits - Pensions and Other [LPEN]] • Asset Retirement Obligation - Non-Current [LARE] • Provision for Environment Obligations - Non-Current [LPVE] • Any other provisions not specifically reported as any of the above (Other Provisions expect Pension & Post Retirement Provisions [LRSV]) • Long-term accreted asset retirement obligations, resulting from the compounding of future site closure costs over the life span of an asset that will be retired, commonly reported by mining companies

i.d: Private Company. Provisions - Non-Current [SNCP] represents the total value of all non-current provisions. It includes provisions for non-current legal costs and litigation claims, for environmental obligations and for future pension liabilities. Applicable to all industries. Provisions - Non-Current [SNCP] includes: • Restructuring Provisions - Non-current [LRSR] • Provision for Litigation-Non current [LLRG] • Provisions - Other - Non-current [SLPO] • Provision for Environment Obligations - Non-Current [LPVE] • Non-current Postemployment Benefits - Pensions and Other [LPEN] • Non-current Provisions – Total – no b/d [LNCU] • Asset Retirement Obligation - Non-current [LARE]

i.d: Private Company. Provisions - Other - Non-current [SLPO] represents other long term provisions. Applicable to all industries. Provisions - Other - Non-current [SLPO] excludes provisions specifically collected under the below FCC’s: • Provision for deferred taxation • Non-Current provisions of post retirement and pension [LPEN] • Asset Retirement Obligation [LARE} • Provision on Litigation [LLGR] • Restructuring Provisions [LRSR] • Provision for Environmental Obligations [LPVE] • Funds for General Banking Risks [LRUL]

Provisions - Other than Pension / Post-Retirement [SPOT] includes: • Restructuring Provisions – Non-Current [LRSR] • Provision for Litigation – Non-Current [LLGR] • Long-term provision for the remediation of natural environment whose value is uncertain and estimated • Other Provisions - Other than Pension/Post Retirement [LRSV] • Non-Current Provisions – Total – No Breakdown [LNCU] • Current Provisions [LCPV] Provisions - Other than Pension / Post-Retirement [SPOT] excludes: • Non-Current Postemployment Benefits - Pensions and Other [LPEN]] • Asset Retirement Obligation - Non-Current [LARE] • Provision for Environment Obligations - Non-Current [LPVE] • Any other provisions not specifically reported as any of the above (Other Provisions expect Pension & Post Retirement Provisions [LRSV]) • Long-term accreted asset retirement obligations, resulting from the compounding of future site closure costs over the life span of an asset that will be retired, commonly reported by mining companies

Provisions - Total [SPROV] represents the sum of all non-current provisions (Provisions - Non-current [SNCP]), all provisions reported under the current liability section except provision for income taxes, deferred taxes (Current Provisions [SCPV]), income taxes estimated and expected to be paid within one year or an operating cycle, whichever is longer (Deferred Income Tax - Current Liability [SDTC]) and the total value of long-term deferred taxes disclosed in the liability section (Deferred Income Tax - LT Liability [SDTL]).

i.d: Private Company. Receivables - Other, Net/Gross [SROT] represents the sum of any receivables other than those generated by sales of products, goods and services, loans and notes receivable, and other receivables represented by specific codes, after provisions for doubtful other receivables. This item include short term accrued income. Receivables - Other, Net/Gross [SROT] includes: • Accrued Income • Accrued Revenue • Accrued Utility Revenues • Ijarah • Mudaraba • Murabaha • Musharaka • Istisna • Wakala • Sukuk • Other Islamic financing receivables • Receivables from/due from employees, officers, directors, or shareholders • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries, if reported outside trade receivables • Due from related parties, if reported outside trade receivables • Receivables from stockholders (gross) Receivables - Other, Net/Gross [SROT] excludes: • Islamic financing products held as investments (Islamic Investments and Deposits [ISID]) • Current unbilled utility revenue (Current Unbilled Utility Revenue - Net/Gross [AUUR]) • Accrued income taxes (Income Tax Receivables - Net/Gross [AOTX]) • Receivables from the sales of products, goods and services (Accounts Receivable, Gross [AARG]) • Non-interest earning receivables from affiliates, associates, joint ventures and subsidiaries, if clearly described as trade receivables, or reported within trade receivables (Accounts Receivable, Gross [AARG]) • Unbilled utility revenue (Current Unbilled Utility Revenue - Net/Gross [AUUR]) • Interest-earning receivables from loans issued and promissory notes receivable (Loan/Notes Receivables, Gross [ALRF]) • Overpaid income tax recoverable from authorities (Income Tax Receivables - Net/Gross [AOTX]) • Credit card receivables (common for retail companies) (Accounts Receivable, Gross [AARG]) • Service contracts receivable (Accounts Receivable, Gross [AARG])

i.d: Private Company. Receivables - Total (excl. Loans) [SRECT] represents the total value of all receivables reported by the company excluding loans and notes receivables. It includes receivables from the sales of products, goods, trading assets (such as inventories) or from services provided, tax recoverable, interest income accrued, but not yet received and for insurance companies receivables from policyholders, agencies, and other operating parties in insurance companies net of impairment , but excludes receivables from reinsurers as well as any other receivables excluding loans. Receivables - Total (excl. Loans) [SRECT] includes: • Other Receivables [SORT] • Accounts and Notes Receivable - Trade, Net/Gross - Non-current [SLAN] • Income Tax Receivables [SITX] • Interest Receivable - Bank [SIRC] • Insurance Premium Receivables [SIPR]

Research and Development Costs, Gross [SRDG] represents the gross value of capitalized expenditure relating to research and development, including the development of new products. Applicable to Industrial companies. Research and Development Costs, Gross [SRDG] includes: • Gross value of capitalized research and development expenditures • In-process Research and Development

Applicable to Industrial companies. Research and Development Costs, Net [SRDN] includes: • Capitalized research and development expenditures • In-process Research and Development

i.d: Private Company. Retained Earnings -Total [SRED] represents the accumulated earnings from operations not distributed to the shareholders or allocated to any reserve account. It may represent accumulated deficit when a company incurs losses over time. Includes an appropriation of profit in some countries based on existing laws or regulations set for a particular company or industry. Applicable to all industries. Retained Earnings -Total [SRED] includes: • Non-distributable Reserves • Other restricted Equity • Reserves not available for distribution • Capital Redemption Reserve • Capital Reserve • Capital Profits and Redemption Reserves • General Capital Reserve • Restricted Reserve • Capital Profits • Goodwill on acquisition • Consolidation difference/Reserve • Reserves arising on consolidation • Goodwill Reserve • Earned Surplus • Profit carried Forward • Retained Earnings/Profits • Unappropriated Retained earnings • Profit/Results brought forward from Previous yrs • Profit and loss account • Undistributed income • Interim dividend • Associated company reserves • Group company reserves • Merger Reserve • Distributions/dividends in excess • Amalgamation Reserve • Legal Reserves • Special Reserves • Statutory Reserve • Reserve under Banking Act/Reconstruction Act • Investment Allowance Reserve under income tax ACT • Statutory and free Reserve • Accumulated distributions in excess of earnings • Dividend in excess of net income Retained Earnings -Total [SRED] excludes: • Capital in excess of par value (Additional Paid in Capital – Common Stock [QPIC]) • Capital Surplus on Preferred Stock [QPFS]

i.d: Private Company. Retained Earnings, Accumulated [SQRED] represents the accumulated earnings from operations not distributed to the shareholders or allocated to any reserve account. It may represent accumulated deficit when a company incurs losses over time. Includes an appropriation of profit in some countries based on existing laws or regulations set for a particular company or industry. Applicable to all industries. Retained Earnings, Accumulated [SQRED] includes: • Non-distributable Reserves • Other restricted Equity • Reserves not available for distribution • Capital Redemption Reserve • Capital Reserve • Capital Profits and Redemption Reserves • General Capital Reserve • Restricted Reserve • Capital Profits • Goodwill on acquisition • Consolidation difference/Reserve • Reserves arising on consolidation • Goodwill Reserve • Earned Surplus • Profit carried Forward • Retained Earnings/Profits • Unappropriated Retained earnings • Profit/Results brought forward from Previous yrs • Profit and loss account • Undistributed income • Interim dividend • Associated company reserves • Group company reserves • Merger Reserve • Distributions/dividends in excess • Amalgamation Reserve • Legal Reserves • Special Reserves • Statutory Reserve • Reserve under Banking Act/Reconstruction Act • Investment Allowance Reserve under income tax ACT • Statutory and free Reserve • Accumulated distributions in excess of earnings • Dividend in excess of net income • General reserves [QGRE] • Other Equity [QOTE] Retained Earnings, Accumulated [SQRED] excludes: • Capital in excess of par value (Additional Paid in Capital – Common Stock [QPIC]) • Capital Surplus on Preferred Stock [QPFS]

Revaluation Reserves [SVLR] includes: • Revaluation Adjustment Fund • Fixed asset Revaluation reserve • Revaluation Reserves • Asset/Investment property Revaluation reserve • Unrealized capital account (Germany) • Surplus from Monetary revaluation of assets • Revaluation provision

i.l: ST Debt & Current Portion of LT Debt (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. ST Debt & Current Portion of LT Debt [SSTD] represents total borrowings that are due within one year. Includes a portion of a long-term debt instrument that is due within the following fiscal year. Applicable to all industries. ST Debt & Current Portion of LT Debt [SSTD] includes: • Short term borrowing and Current portion of long debt • Total short term borrowing (which includes current maturities) • Convertible Subordinated Debentures/Notes/Loans/Bonds • Term Loans • Recourse/Non-Recourse Debt • Mortgage Obligations/Notes/Loans for Real Estate companies • Convertible Notes/Bonds/Debentures • Debentures for Redemption • Bonds • Current portion of long term debt and Capitalized leases • Last installment of Long term debt • Current Portion of capital Leases (Current Portion of Capital Leases [LCFL]) ST Debt & Current Portion of LT Debt [SSTD] excludes: • Notes payable (Short Term Debt and Notes Payable [LSOD]) • Current maturities (Current Portion of LT Debt/Capital Leases [LCLD]) • Combination of only Current maturities (Current Portion of LT Debt/Capital Leases [LCLD]) • Current Hybrid bond (Current Hybrid Financial Instrument - Liability [LCHU]) • Current Derivative Liabilities – Hedging (or if co does not specific Hedging or Trading) – (Current Derivative Liabilities - Hedging [LCDV]) • Trading liabilities –non interest bearing (update to LTRL under current liabilities. Update to LOLL if reported under non-differentiated method) • Acceptance (under payables)- (Accounts Payable [LAPB]) • Combination of only Short term Debt items (ST Debt & Notes Payable [LSOD]) • Trading liabilities – interest bearing reported under current liabilities. (If company is silent about interest bearing or if non-interest cannot be bifurcated then update it to Trading Account Liabilities [LTRL] under current liabilities. Update to LOLL if reported under non-differentiated method) (ST Debt & Notes Payable [LSOD]) • Acceptance (interest bearing or standalone) (ST Debt & Notes Payable [LSOD])

i.d: Private Company. ST Debt & Notes Payable [SSOD] refers to short term debt, notes payable, bills of exchange and other interest-bearing debt obligations due within a year. Applicable to all industries. ST Debt & Notes Payable [SSOD] includes: • Short term borrowings from banks/lines of credit/credit facility/financing facility, bank overdrafts, commercial paper, due to banks in non-banking financial service companies • Notes payable/promissory notes/posted dated cheques to third parties or affiliates reported outside trade/accounts payable • Demand notes payable, loans payable, mortgages payable, mortgage notes (short-term) • Revolving credit/loans (short-term) ST Debt & Notes Payable [SSOD] excludes: • Current portion of long-term debt (classified as Current Portion of LT Debt/Capital Leases [LCLD] • Capital leases payable when reported as a part of current liabilities (classified as Current Portion of LT Debt/Capital Leases [LCLD]) • Current portion of Hybrid financial instrument – liability (classified as Current Hybrid Financial Instrument - Liability - Total - no b/d [LCHU]) • Current portion of Coupon bonds, bridge loans/notes, convertible bonds/debentures/notes payable, acquisition notes, subordinated debt/notes/debenture/bonds, senior notes/loans when reported as a part of current liabilities (classified as Current Portion of LT Debt/Capital Leases [LCLD]) • Interest accrued/payable (LSIP) • Short-term interest-bearing speculative/trading derivatives (LDSC) • Short-term interest-bearing hedging derivatives (LCDV) • Short-term derivative liabilities not specified as hedging or trading/speculative, for industrial and property companies (Current Derivative Liabilities – Hedging [LCDV]) • Due to related parties (Accounts Payable [LAPB] if clearly described as trade payables or reported within trade accounts, or as Other Payables LOPB] if reported outside trade payables) • Due to shareholders/officers/directors/employees (Other Payables [LOPB]) unless they are interest bearing.

i.d: Private Company. ST Debt excl. Collateralized Financing [SDXF] represents short-term borrowings and interest-bearing liabilities reported by a bank other than collateralized financing instruments. Applicable to Banks. ST Debt excl. Collateralized Financing [SDXF] includes • Bills of Exchange and Notes [LBLS] • Other Short Term Borrowings [LSTB] ST Debt excl. Collateralized Financing [SDXF] excludes: • Federal Funds Purchased and Securities Sold under Repurchase Agreements [LFSR] • Securities Sold under Repurchase Agreements [LSRP] • Federal Funds Purchased [LFFP] • Securities Loaned [LSCL] • Long-term or non-differentiated interest due and payable on deposit accounts and debt, but not yet paid (classified as Accrued Interest [LAAI]). • Short-term accrued interest on current debt (Interest Payable - Short Term Debt [LSIP])

i.d: Private Company. ST Investments [ASTI] represents investments in debt and equity securities with maturity of one year or less. The “short-term” nature depends on actual maturity of one year from the balance sheet date rather than on the original maturity of a specific investment. Applicable to Industrial, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. ST Investments [ASTI] includes: • Securities maturing within less than one year • Shares and similar Investments • Bonds and similar Investments • Investment in fixed deposits • Investment in debt securities • Short-term investment • Certificates of deposits • Short-term papers • Trading account securities in investment services and miscellaneous financial services ST Investments [ASTI] excludes: • Cash and Cash deposits in Bank (Cash [ACSH]) • Restricted Cash (Restricted Accounts - Current [ARCA]) • Money Market Fund (Cash & Equivalents [ACAE]) • Receivables from financial leases (Loans & Notes Receivables, Net [ACLR]) • Receivables from financial leases (Finance Lease Receivables, Net [ACFR]) • Receivables from sale-type leases related to the gain on the sale of an asset (Accounts Receivable, Net [AACR]) • Interest receivable from sale-type leases (Loans & Notes Receivables, Net [ACLR])

i.d: Private Company. ST Investments - Total [SSTI] consists of any investments in debt and equity securities with maturity of one year or less. The “short-term” nature depends on actual maturity of one year from the balance sheet date rather than on the original maturity of a specific investment. Includes derivative instruments held in the trading account, for investment or speculative purposes, disclosed as part of short-term receivables. ST Investments - Total [SSTI] Includes: • Securities maturing within less than one year • Shares and similar Investments • Bonds and similar Investments • Investment in fixed deposits • Investment in debt securities • Short-term investment • Certificates of deposits • Short-term Papers • Trading account securities in investment services and miscellaneous financial services ST Investments - Total [SSTI] excludes: Fair value of derivative financial instruments held for trading/investment purposes • Forward exchange contracts (If it’s a part of financial assets) • Foreign currency options (If it’s a part of financial assets) • Derivative short –term investments • Derivatives on commodity contracts, when reported as part of investments ST Investments - Total [SSTI] excludes: • Cash & Cash deposits in Bank [ACSH] • Restricted Cash/investment as a part • Money Market Fund [ACAE] • Receivables from financial leases reported by industrial and property companies [ACLR] • Receivables from financial leases reported by capital lease companies [ACFR] • Receivables from sale-type leases related to the gain on the sale of an asset [AACR] • Interest receivable from sale-type leases [ACLR] • Short Term Loans [AST] • Trading account securities in investment services and miscellaneous financial services Investment assets other than trading account assets in investment services and miscellaneous financial services companies. • Current hedging assets disclosed within receivables (Current Derivative Financial Instruments - Hedging in Receivables [ARCD]) – reported by Industrial and Property companies • Speculative derivative assets held by Bank, Insurance, Investment and Financial companies (Trading Account Assets [ATAA]) • Short term Loan [classified as ACLR] • Restricted short-term derivative investments [classified as ARCA]

i.d: Private Company. Total Cash & Deposits [SCDIS] represents the sum of cash and short term investments [SCSTI], total Islamic debt [SISD], all receivables arising from Islamic specific financing agreements [ISRC], deposits that bear interest and are not repayable on demand [SNID], securities classified as designated at fair value through profit and loss,but not further classified as available for sale (AFS), held to maturity (HTM) or for trading [SOFV] and short-term loans with banks repayable upon demand [SMMP] Total Cash & Deposits [SCDIS] includes: • Cash & Cash Equivalents combined with short-term investments • Liquid Assets combined with short-term investments • Due from other banks • Short term deposits (non-interest earning) made by the bank in other banks for services rendered. • Checks not yet cleared by the Federal Reserve Board • Items in the course of collection • Balances with central bank, if not delineated separately • Saving accounts – not specified as made by banks or customers • Time deposits or term deposits – not specified as made by banks or customers • Certificates of deposits – not specified as made by banks or customers • Securities at fair value through profit or loss • Call/demand loans receivable • Demand note receivable from a bank • Callable securities other than callable instruments • Money at short notice Total Cash & Deposits [SCDIS] excludes: • Cash & cash-equivalents reported separately (Cash & Equivalents [ACAE]) • Cash in hand (Cash [ACSH]) • Cash at Bank (Cash [ACSH]) • Short Term Investment (ST Investments [ASTI]) • Restricted Cash (Restricted Accounts - Current [ARCA]) • Money Market Funds (Cash & Equivalents [ACAE]) • Balance with Central Banks [ABCB] • Vault cash (Balance with Central Banks [ABCB]) • Lending & LT Deposits Due from Banks [ADBU] • Time and interest-earning deposits receivable from other financial institutions (Time Deposits [ABTD]) • Interbank loans receivable (Bank Loans, Gross [AGLB] or Bank Loans, Net [ANLB]) • Notes & Bills [ACNO] • Money at Call [ACMY] • Cash & Equivalents [ACAE] • Cash [ACSH] • Segregated Cash Deposits [ACCD], reported by consumer loan and other financial companies • Short-term deposits reported by Industrial and Property companies (ST Investments [ASTI]) • Net financial income other than interest income from financial assets • Interest Bearing Demand Deposits - Banks (Interest Bearing Demand Deposits - to Banks and Financial Institutions [LIDB]) • Non-interest Bearing Demand Deposits – Banks (Non-interest Bearing Demand Deposits - to Banks and Financial Institutions [LNDB]) • Deposits from Customers - Total - no b/d (Deposits from Customers - Total - no b/d [LDBC]) • Investment Securities Available for Sale [ASFS] • Securities Held to Maturity [ASHM] • Securities held for trading (Trading Account Assets [ATAA])

i.d: Private Company. Capital Expenditures - Total [SCEX] encompass all expenditures for factories, equipment, software development costs and intangible assets that have a useful life of more than one year. These expenditures are not treated as an expense on the income statement when they are incurred. Rather, they are capitalized, meaning that they are expensed over time. Capital Expenditures consist of expenditures that are necessary to maintain the existing plant and equipment in premium condition, and discretionary expenditures for growth. Applicable to all industries. Capital Expenditures – Total [SCEX] includes: • Acquisition of patents, copyrights, trademarks, customer lists, domain names, distribution rights, brands • Acquisition of goodwill • Acquisition of cellular licenses for telecommunication service companies • Expenditure on/acquisition of film libraries for motion picture companies • Franchise agreements • Mortgage servicing rights for banks • Film production costs capitalized [IIAQ] • Capitalized software development costs • Website development costs • Increase in fixed assets held under long-term capital leases • Increase in airplanes under capital leases for airline companies • Increase in aircraft for rent in aerospace companies • Deposits for aircraft acquisition for airline companies • Purchase of mining properties/mineral properties for mining companies • Expenditure on nuclear fuel for electric utility companies • Recurring/non-recurring capital expenditures • Satellite construction for broadcasting companies • Purchase of software that is an integral part of equipment • Purchase of leased assets, reported by financial leasing companies • Lease capital expenditure Capital Expenditures – Total [SCEX] excludes: • Acquisition of investments [IINP] • Increase in assets for sale (classified as Purchase of Investments [IINP]) • Increase in assets to be leased out under long-term finance lease, which results in an increase in loans to customers ([OACR]-reported in the operating section) or ([IINP]-reported in the investing section) • Increase in fixed assets of discontinued operations (Discontinued Operations - Investing [IDIN]) • Acquisition of business units (Acquisition of Business [IBAQ]) • Acquisition of affiliate companies (Purchase of Investment Securities - Unclassified [IINP]) • Increase in organization costs (Other Investing Cash Flow [IICF])

i.d: Private Company. Capital Expenditures, Net [SCAP] represents all expenditures for factories and equipment that have a useful life of more than one year. These expenditures are not treated as an expense on the income statement when they are incurred. Rather, they are capitalized, meaning that they are expensed over time. Capital Expenditures consist of expenditures that are necessary to maintain the existing plant and equipment in premium condition and discretionary expenditures for growth. Includes tangible and intangible assets as well as investment property. Applicable to all industries. Capital Expenditures, Net [SCAP] includes: • Sale/disposition of trademarks, broadcasting licenses, patents, copyrights, service rights, capitalized software development costs, etc. • Acquisition of patents, copyrights, trademarks, customer lists, domain names, distribution rights, brands • Acquisition of goodwill • Acquisition of cellular licenses for telecommunication service companies • Expenditure on/acquisition of film libraries for motion picture companies • Franchise agreements • Mortgage servicing rights for banks • Film production costs capitalized [IIAQ] • Capitalized software development costs • Website development costs • Acquisition or disposal of property, plant and equipment when reported as a combined line item • Net purchase/sale of investment properties • Total cash inflows and outflows related to investment properties, such as purchases of new investment properties, improvements to existing investment property, construction costs associated with developing investment property and sale of investment property • Net purchase/sale of land or buildings held to be leased out under operating lease, where the lessor is not actively using this land or building for the production of goods or supply of services, or for administration (the lessor is a passive investor) • Net purchase/sale of land or buildings held with a view to long-term capital appreciation • Net purchase/disposal of land or buildings held for undetermined future use • Net purchase/sale of Real Estate with no distinction between rental and own use Capital Expenditures, Net [SCAP] excludes: • Disposition of deferred charges [IICF] • Acquisition of software for software development companies ISDC] • Expenditure on/acquisition of software as an integral part of property, plant &equipment [ICEX] • Acquisition of investments [IINP] • Acquisition of lease equipment [IPLP] • Expenditure on organization costs [IICF] • Net acquisition/disposal of subsidiaries engaged in property business (Acquisition/Sale of Business, Net [IBAS])

i.d: Private Company. Cash Dividends Paid – Common [SPDC] represents cash dividends paid to common stockholders. This amount may be different from the dividends declared in the same period. Although the distribution of stock to shareholders as stock dividends or bonus shares is a non-cash activity, companies may report the stock dividend as cash distribution and an increase in common stock. In such cases, Thomson Reuters follows what was reported by the company. Applicable to all industries. Cash Dividends Paid – Common [SPDC] includes: • Distribution to shareholders, unit holders, parent company • Ordinary dividends, special dividends, memorial dividends to common stock Cash Dividends Paid – Common [SPDC] excludes: • Distribution to minority shareholders of subsidiaries, general partners [Dividends Paid to Minority Interest [FDMI]) The same root tag is used in the financing and supplemental section. The company does not have any preferred shares, hence reported dividends in the cash flow is updated to more specific FCC – common dividends.

i.d: Private Company. Total Cash Dividends Paid [SCDP] represents the total value of cash dividends paid to shareholders. Although the distribution of stock to shareholders as stock dividends or bonus shares is a non-cash activity, certain companies may report the stock dividend as a cash distribution and an increase in common stock. In such cases, Thomson Reuters follows what was reported by the company. Always cross-check the Balance sheet for the availability of preferred stock and also the Shareholder’s Equity Table. Suppose there is no preferred stock, then the reported cash dividends can be coded to common dividends. The distribution is generally made quarterly in the form of cash (cash dividend), but as mentioned above, it can also take the form of stock (stock dividend). Dividends to shareholders may consist of ordinary dividends, special dividends, etc. Applicable to all industries. Total Cash Dividends Paid [SCDP] includes: • Cash paid in lieu of fractional shares • Special dividends • Stock dividends (when not segregated) • Preferred or common distributions when reported as a combined value and cannot be broken • Distribution to shareholders, unit holders, parent company

i.d: Private Company. Depreciation incl. in COGS [SDCS] represents the accounting process of allocating the cost of tangible fixed assets to expenses over those periods expected to benefit from the use of the assets reported within the cost of sales. Applicable to Industrial, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. Depreciation incl. in COGS [SDCS] includes: • Depreciation of tangible fixed assets (land, property, equipment and other assets classified as tangibles on the balance sheet) • Depreciation of natural resources which are classified as tangible fixed assets in the balance sheet • Depletion • Depreciation of utility plant • Depreciation of biological assets reported within the cost of sales for companies reporting a by-function breakdown of income statement expenses • Accelerated depreciation in cost of sales • Impairment of tangible assets if not delineated separately • Combined depreciation and amortization reported within cost of sales, for companies reporting a by-function breakdown of income statement expenses • Impairment of tangible or intangible assets if not delineated separately Depreciation incl. in COGS [SDCS] excludes: • Depreciation of investment property [EDEI] if disclosed on the face of income statement or in the breakout, or as Depreciation of Investment Properties [VDEI] if the value cannot be broken out on the face • Impairments if they can be broken out • Amortization of intangible assets (Amortization of Intangibles [EAMI]) • Depreciation included in other functional categories of income statement expenses (Depreciation/Amortization in Selling, General and Administration [EDAS] or Depreciation & Amortization in Research and Development [EDAR]) • Any depreciation or depletion for companies reporting a by-nature breakdown of income statement expenses (not grouped into functional categories) (Depreciation [EDEP])

Applicable to all industries. Depreciation incl. in SGA [SDES] includes: • Depreciation of tangible fixed assets (land, property, equipment and other assets classified as tangibles on the balance sheet) • Depreciation of natural resources which are classified as tangible fixed assets in the balance sheet • Depletion reported within the selling, general and administrative expenses for companies reporting a by-function breakdown of income statement expenses • Accelerated depreciation in SGA expenses • Impairment of tangible assets if not delineated separately • Combined depreciation and amortization reported within selling, general and administrative expenses for companies reporting a by-function breakdown of income statement expenses (Depreciation/Amortization in SGA [EDAS] • Depretiation in Research & Development [EDRD] • Combined Depreciation and Amortization in Research & Development [EDAR] Depreciation incl. in SGA [SDES] excludes: • Depreciation of investment property [EDEI] if disclosed on the face of income statement or in the breakout, or as Depreciation of Investment Properties [VDEI] if the value cannot be broken out on the face • Impairments if they can be broken out • Amortization of intangible assets • Depreciation included in other functional category of income statement expenses (Depreciation in COR/COGS [EDEC]) • Any depreciation or depletion for companies reporting a by-nature breakdown of income statement expenses (not grouped into functional categories) (Depreciation [EDEP])

i.d: Private Company. Depreciation & Amortization [EDAE] represents the amount charged for the combined depreciation of tangible fixed assets and amortization of intangibles during the period, reported outside cost of sales. This item is applicable to all industries and may also be reported as part of the business and geographic segment information. Depreciation & Amortization [EDAE] includes: • Combined depreciation and amortization reported outside cost of sales, for companies reporting a by-function breakdown of income statement expenses • Combined depreciation and amortization for companies reporting a by-nature breakdown of income statement expenses (not grouped into functional categories) • Impairment of tangible or intangible assets if not delineated separately Depreciation & Amortization [EDAE] excludes: • Impairments if delineated separately (Impairment of Fixed Assets [EIFO]) • Amortization of intangible assets if delineated separately (Amortization of Intangibles [EAMI]) • Depreciation of tangible fixed assets if delineated separately (Depreciation [EDEP]) • Depreciation or amortization included in one of the functional categories of income statement expenses (Depreciation & Amortization incl. in SGA [EDAS]or Depreciation & Amortization in Research and Development [EDAR])

i.d: Private Company. Dilution Adjustment [CDAJ] represents the adding back to reported net income of the interest expense of debentures when assumed converted, and the adding back to the reported net income of the convertible preferred dividends when assumed converted. The adjustment is used to calculate Diluted EPS. Applicable to all industries. Dilution Adjustment [CDAJ] excludes: • U.S. GAAP adjustment [CGAP] • After-tax adjustments applied to net earnings that are used to calculate a company’s earnings per share, other than dilution adjustment and the U.S. GAAP adjustment (Other Adjustments to Net Income [COAJ])

i.d: Private Company. Distribution for Preferential Shares [SDFS] represents the total monetary amount of the current dividend requirement on issued preferred stock of a company (including its subsidiaries). Preferred stockholders normally forgo voting rights and receive a fixed dividend that takes precedence over the payment of dividends to common stockholders. Preferred dividends are usually cumulative and non-participative in nature. When preferred stock is redeemed during the year, the company may still report preferred dividends on the income statement, although there is no preferred stock outstanding at the end of that fiscal year. Applicable to all industries. Distribution for Preferential Shares [SDFS] includes: • Dividends on preferred stock • Income Allocable to Participating securities • Dividend requirement on preference shares • Accredited/declared/deemed/imputed dividends to preferred stocks • Issuance of additional shares (preferred or common) in lieu of cash dividend to preferred stocks (considered to be equivalent to cash dividends to the preferred stock) • Preferred dividends of a subsidiary • Income allocable to common shareholders to reflect participation rights of the company's convertible preferred stock. This applies to markets where convertible preferred stock are treated as preferred shares, and usually results in a difference between Net Income Available to Common Shareholders and Net Income Allocable to Common Shareholders Distribution for Preferential Shares [SDFS] excludes: • Interest Expense on Hybrid Debt Instruments – Equity [CHDE] • General partners’ interest (Distribution for General Partners [CGPD]) • Distribution to limited partners (Dividends Provided or Paid – Common [DPDC]) • Other adjustments to earnings for EPS computation (Other Adjustments to Net Income [COAJ])

i.d: Private Company. Excise Tax Expense [REXT] represents a government-levied tax on the manufacture, sale, or consumption of goods and services included in the sale price, collected by the seller, and returned to the government. The tax can be imposed at any trade level and can either be a specific tax or a value-added tax (percentage of value). Thomson Reuters uses excise taxes receipts only when receipts of excise taxes are clearly identified as revenue in the income statement of a company. (In most cases, this item appears twice, once as income (collected from customers) and as expense (paid to the government). Applicable to Industrial companies. Excise Tax Expense [REXT] includes: • Sales and excise taxes and duties reported outside gross revenues • Excise/sales taxes, VAT • Sales Tax • Business Tax • Operating Tax • Consumption Tax • VAT • Coal resource tax (Coal business) • General and services tax • Windfall profit taxes • Ad valorem taxes • Domestic international sales corporation taxes Excise Tax Expense [REXT] excludes: • Excise taxes reported within gross revenues (before subtracting from the gross value of sales) (Gross Turnover [RREV]) • Sales allowances for clients and distributors, sales returns, and other adjustment decreasing the value of gross sales (Allowances, Returns and Other Adjustments [RSRT])

i.d: Private Company. Extraordinary Activities [SXTR] represents events and transactions that are distinguished by their unusual nature, by the infrequency of their occurrence, and the materiality of their impact on the earnings of the company, reported after income taxes. This item is applicable to all industries and may also be reported as part of the business and geographic segment information. Extraordinary Activities [SXTR] includes: • Extraordinary items before their tax impact, if broken out into pre-tax values and tax impacts • Net extraordinary items after the tax impact, if gross values are not available • Impact of natural disasters • Impact of terrorist attacks • Impact of changes in accounting standards, if combined with other extraordinary activities • Other non-recurring and extraordinary items Extraordinary Activities [SXTR] excludes: • Impact of changes in accounting standards, when reported separately from other extraordinary activities (Impacts from Changes in Accounting Standards [XACG]) • Result from current discontinued operations and gain/loss on sale discontinued operations
