i.d: Private Company. Impairment of Fixed Assets [EIFO] represents a non-recurring item related to the unexpected and unplanned value write-down of long-lived assets or assets held for use. These assets are retained by the reporting company. This item is applicable to all industries and may also be reported as part of the business and geographic segment information. Impairment of Fixed Assets [EIFO] includes: • Impairment/write-down/write-off/write-up of long-term assets • Revaluation of long-term assets, where the term “revaluation” or “value change” refers to an unplanned value write-down of an asset • Impairment of long-term assets that are not specified as tangible, intangible, goodwill or other long-term asset types Impairment of Fixed Assets [EIFO] excludes: • Unrealized gains and losses on the fair value change of investment property (Fair Value Adjustments on Investment Property [EIPV]), financial investments (Fair Value Adjustments of Financial Investments [EFVI]), biological assets (Fair Value Adjustments on Biological Assets [EFVB]) and other assets (Fair Value Adjustments on Other Assets [EFVO]) where the fair value change is not related to exceptional write-downs or write-ups • Depreciation of fixed assets, i.e. value loss that is part of a regular depreciation schedule • Revaluation of investment property, financial investments, biological assets and other assets, where the term “revaluation” or “value change” refers to fair value change that is not related to exceptional write-downs or write-ups • Impairment of Financial Investments [EIVO] • Write-down of exploration (dry hole) expenses by oil and natural gas extraction companies (Exploration/Dry Hole Expenses (including Write Off) [EEXP]) • Other Than Temporary Impairment Losses on Investments [RIMP] • Revaluation of trading derivatives for non-financial companies (Gains/Losses on Trading Derivatives [EDTR]) • Unrealized gains and losses on the fair value change of hedging derivatives (Fair Value/Unrealized Adjustments on Derivatives for Hedging [EDEO])

i.l: Impairment of Tangible & Intangible Fixed Assets (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. Impairment of Tangible & Intangible Fixed Assets [SITI] represents the total value of impairment of all assets. It includes a non-recurring item related to the unexpected and unplanned value write-down of long-lived assets or assets held for use, company acquisition costs (goodwill), other intangible assets and oil and natural gas assets. Applicable to all industries. Impairment of Tangible & Intangible Fixed Assets [SITI] includes: • Impairment/write-down/write-off/write-up of long-term assets. • Revaluation of long-term assets, where the term “revaluation” or “value change” refers to an unplanned value write-down of an asset. • Impairment of long-term assets that are not specified as tangible, intangible, goodwill or other long-term asset types • Impairment/write-down/write-off/write-up of goodwill • Revaluation of goodwill, where the term “revaluation” or “value change” refers to an unplanned value write-down • Impairment/write-down/write-off/write-up of intangible assets other than goodwill • Revaluation of intangible assets other than goodwill, where the term “revaluation” or “value change” refers to an unplanned value write-down • Impairment of intangible assets that are not specified as including or excluding goodwill • Impairment/write-down/write-off/write-up of natural gas and oil assets by extraction companies that is not related to its regular unsuccessful drilling operations • Revaluation of oil and gas assets, where the term “revaluation” or “value change” refers to an unplanned value write-down • Impairment of capitalized exploration and evaluation costs, mineral properties, or oil and gas properties Impairment of Tangible & Intangible Fixed Assets [SITI] excludes: • Unrealized gains and losses on the fair value change of investment property (EIPV), financial investments (EFVI), biological assets (EFVB) and other assets (EFVO) where the fair value change is not related to exceptional write-downs or write-ups • Depreciation of fixed assets, i.e. value loss that is part of a regular depreciation schedule • Revaluation of investment property, financial investments, biological assets and other assets, where the term “revaluation” or “value change” refers to fair value change that is not related to exceptional write-downs or write-ups • Impairment of financial investments (EIVO) • Other-than-temporary investment losses (RIMP) • Revaluation of trading derivatives for non-financial companies (Gains/Losses on Trading Derivatives [EDTR]) • Unrealized gains and losses on the fair value change of hedging derivatives (EDEO) • Amortization of goodwill, i.e. value loss that is part of a regular amortization schedule • Amortization of intangible assets other than goodwill, i.e. value loss that is part of a regular amortization schedule • Write-down of exploration (dry hole) expenses by oil and natural gas extraction companies (Exploration/Dry Hole Expenses (Incl Write Off) [EEXP]). Dry hole expenses refer to regular unsuccessful exploration activities and thus are not considered as unusual/unplanned impairment. • Depreciation or amortization of oil and gas assets, i.e. value loss that is part of a regular depreciation or amortization schedule

i.d: Private Company. Income Available to Common Shares [SNIS] represents total net income/loss reported by the company after provision for income taxes, equity in earnings, after-tax adjustments, discontinued operations, extraordinary items and minority interest, but before other adjustments to net income, preferred dividends and other distributions (Net Income Including Extra Items [XNIC]) adjusted by: • Policyholders Surplus [SPHS] • Other Earnings Adjustments to Net Income [SOAJ] • Net Income After Minority Interest [SNIC] • Distribution for General Partners [SDSP] •Distribution for Preferential Shares [SDFS] • Interest Expense on Hybrid Debt Instruments – Equity [CHDE]

i.l: Income Before Discont Operations & Extraord Items (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. Income Before Discontinued Operations & Extraordinary Items [SICO] represents a sum of the income/expense after all operating and non-operating income and expense, reserves, income taxes but before equity in earnings, minority interest, extraordinary items, after-tax adjustments, discontinued operations and preferred dividends (Net Income after Tax [SIAT]), the share of earnings/losses that the company is entitled to from unconsolidated affiliated companies which has not been distributed as dividends (Equity in Earnings of Affiliates (after Taxes) [SQEA]) and adjustments to net income reported after taxes but before equity in earnings, minority interest, extraordinary items, discontinued operations and preferred dividends (Other Adjustments after Taxes - Total [SOAN]). Applicable to all industries. Income Before Discontinued Operations & Extraordinary Items [SICO] is a sum of: • Equity in Earnings of Affiliates (after Taxes) [SQEA] • Other Adjustments after Taxes - Total [SOAN] • Net Income after Tax [SIAT]

i.d: Private Company. Income Before Taxes [SIBT] represents as reported income/loss after all operating and non-operating income and expense, before the deduction of income tax. Applicable to all industries. Income Before Taxes [SIBT] includes: • Profit before tax • Profit before appropriations and tax • Net Income before income Tax/ Extraordinary Items • Net income before Income Tax/Minority Interest/Equity in affiliates • Net Income before Income tax/Preferred Dividend • Net Income before Income tax/Minority Interest/equity in affiliates/Extraordinary Items/Preferred Dividend • Net Income before Income tax/ Distribution for General Partners/ Distribution for Preferential Shares Income Before Taxes [SIBT] excludes: • For companies reporting Profit before tax as the bottom line of the income statement, i.e. not reporting income tax/net income, Net Income Before Tax [XIBT] would be considered as Net Income.

Income Taxes [STAX] includes: • Tax provisions • Any other income tax break outs Income Taxes [STAX] excludes: • Taxes reported within revenues, operating income/expenses and non-operating items

i.l: Interest Expense - Net of Capitalized Interest (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. Interest Expense - Net of Capitalized Interest [SIEN] represents interest expense on debt, net of interest capitalized. Applicable to Industrial, Insurance, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies and may also be reported as part of the business and geographic segment information. Interest Expense - Net of Capitalized Interest [SIEN] includes: • Interest expense that is not specified as before or after interest capitalized • Interest expense net of interest capitalized Interest Expense - Net of Capitalized Interest [SIEN] excludes: • Interest Capitalized [ECAP] • Bank interest expenses reported as part of net interest income/expenses (Total Interest Expense - Business –Total (No b/d) [EIEU], Customer Interest [EBCU], Interest Expense on Collateralized Financing [EFFS], Interest on Trading Liabilities [EETL], Interest Expense on Operational Financing - Business – Total (No b/d) [EBMI], Other Interest Expenses [EEOI], Dividends on hybrid financial instruments - liability portion [EPRD], Interest on Other Borrowings [EIEF], Return on Unrestricted Investment Accounts [ERUI])

i.l: Interest Expenses on Capital Financing, Gross (Pvt)
i.d: Private Company. Interest Expenses on Capital Financing, Gross [ETIE] represents interest expense on debt before interest capitalized. When not reported, Thomson Reuters calculates the gross value from the reported net and capitalized values. Applicable to Industrial, Insurance, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. Interest Expenses on Capital Financing, Gross [ETIE] includes: • Interest expense before deduction of capitalized interest • Amortization of debt Interest Expenses on Capital Financing, Gross [ETIE] excludes: • Interest expense that is not specified as before or after interest capitalized (Interest Expense - Net of Capitalized Interest [EIEN]) • Bank interest expenses reported as part of net interest income/expenses (Total Interest Expense - Business –Total (No Break-down) [EIEU], Customer Interest [EBCU], Interest Expense on Collateralized Financing [EFFS], Interest on Trading Liabilities [EETL], Interest Expense on Operational Financing - Business – Total (No Break-down) [EBMI], Other Interest Expenses [EEOI], Dividends on Hybrid Financial Instruments - Liability Portion [EPRD], Interest on Other Borrowings [EIEF], Return on Unrestricted Investment Accounts [ERUI])

Interest received from advances, deposit accounts. Applicable to Industrial, Insurance, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. Interest Income - Non Bank [EIIN] includes: • For industrial and property companies - any interest income • For insurance, investment and financial companies - interest income that does not form part of a company’s core operations, disclosed outside revenues, investment income or net interest income • Interest income on debt receivables Interest Income - Non Bank [EIIN] excludes: • Bank interest and dividend income reported as part of net interest income (Interest and Fees on Loans [RFLI], Interest Income on Collateralized Financing [RTSF], Bank Interest [RTBK], Interest Income on Loans - Business – Total (No b/d) [RIIU], Interest and Dividend Income on Trading Account Assets [RVTA], Interest and Dividends on Investment Securities Available for Sale/Held to Maturity [RISI], Interest and Dividend Income on Investment Securities - Business - Total (No b/d) [RDIU]) • Interest and dividend income reported by investment companies in the revenue or investment income sections (Dividend Income - Investment [RNID], Interest Income - Investment [RNIT], Interest and Dividend Income - Finance, Total/No Breakdown [RIDU]) • Interest and dividend income reported by insurance companies in the revenue or total income sections (Investment Income, Gross - Insurance [RIIT], Investment Income, Net - Insurance [RNII]) • Interest and dividend income reported by other financial companies as part of net interest income (Interest and Dividend Income - Finance, Total/No Breakdown [RIDU], Interest and Fees on Loans [RFLI], Interest Income on Loans - Business – Total (No b/d) [RIIU], Interest and Dividend Income on Trading Account Assets [RVTA], Interest and Dividends on Investment Securities Available for Sale/Held to Maturity [RISI], Interest and Dividend Income on Investment Securities - Business - Total (No b/d) [RDIU], Other Interest or Dividend Income [ROID])

i.d: Private Company. Investment Gain/ (Loss) [SINVG] represents realized gains and losses on the sale of investments held for sale, maturity and trading. It includes interest from investments together with any income received on short term lending. Applicable to Industrial, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. Investment Gain/ (Loss) [SINVG includes: • Investment income and expenses of non-financial companies, when a company does not specify whether the gains/losses result from revaluation (unrealized gains) or sale (realized gains) • For industrial and property companies - any interest income • For insurance, investment and financial companies - interest income that does not form part of a company’s core operations, disclosed outside revenues, investment income or net interest income • Interest income on debt receivables Investment Gain/ (Loss) [SINVG excludes: • Fair value adjustments/revaluation of financial investments (Fair Value Adjustments of Financial Investments[EFVI]) • Realized gains and losses on the sale of investments reported by bank and insurance companies • Gains/losses on the sale of businesses, affiliates, unconsolidated subsidiaries, joint ventures, consolidated subsidiaries, which are likely one-time holdings of a large stake of the investee (Gain/Loss on Sale and Acquisition of Group Companies [EDSA]) • Gains/Losses on Sale of Tangible and Intangible Fixed Assets [EGFA] • Sale of investment properties (Gain/Loss on Sale of Investment Properties – Property [ESLP]) • Result on the sale of speculative derivatives for non-financial companies (Gains/Losses on Trading Derivatives [EDTR]) • Sale of hedging derivatives (Realized Gain/Loss on Derivatives - Hedging [EDRG]) • Dividend /Investment income [EIDT] • Equity earnings/losses on affiliates, unconsolidated subsidiaries, partnerships, or joint ventures (before taxes – Equity Earnings - Before Taxes [EIQA]] • Fair Value Adjustments on Investment Property [EIPV], Fair Value Adjustments on Biological Assets [EFVB] and Fair Value Adjustments on Other Assets [EFVO] • Foreign currency gains/losses (Foreign Exchange Gain/Loss [EIFX]) • Impairment of Investment Property [EINP] • Impairment of financial investments (Impairment of Financial Investments [EIVO] or Other Than Temporary Impairment Losses on Investments [RIMP]) • Bank interest and dividend income reported as part of net interest income (Interest and Fees on Loans [RFLI], Interest Income on Collateralized Financing [RTSF], Bank Interest [RTBK], Interest Income on Loans - Business - Total (No b/d) [RDIU]) • Interest and dividend income reported by investment companies in the revenue or investment income sections (Dividend Income - Investment [RNID], Interest Income - Investment [RNIT], Interest and Dividend Income - Finance, Total/No Breakdown [RIDU]) • Interest and dividend income reported by insurance companies in the revenue or total income sections (Investment Income, Gross - Insurance [RIIT], Investment Income, Net - Insurance [RNII]) • Interest and dividend income reported by other financial companies as part of net interest income (Interest and Dividend Income - Finance, Total/No Breakdown [RIDU], Interest and Fees on Loans [RFLI], Interest Income on Loans - Business – Total (No b/d) [RIIU], Interest and Dividend Income on Trading Account Assets [RVTA], Interest and Dividends on Investment Securities Available for Sale/Held to Maturity [RISI], Interest and Dividend Income on Investment Securities - Labor & Related Expenses in SGA [ELAS] represents expenses paid to employees of a company in the form of salaries, wages, fees, benefits or any other form of compensation reported within the selling, general and administrative expenses. Litigation Expenses & Settlements [SLIT] represents a difference between non-recurring litigation expenses and legal/litigation provisions and the total value of net non-recurring income or losses, reported before taxes. i.d: Private Company. Material Expenses [SMAT] represents the total of all direct material costs of goods and services sold. Applicable to Industrial companies. Material Expenses [SMAT] includes: • Specific material costs when not reported separately: materials purchased, changes in inventory, work in progress, own work capitalized and utility power/fuel costs • Direct property expenses, rental costs • Nuclear fuel purchased for power plants • Materials purchased when reported as a standalone item (Materials Purchased [EPRW]) • Electric power purchased for resale (Purchased Power [EPPR]) • Natural gas purchased for resale (Fuel Purchased for Resale [EFPR]) • Capitalized own production of property, plant and equipment • Company-produced additions to plant and equipment • Capitalized production • Write-down or write-up of provisions for expected value diminution of finished goods, raw materials and work in progress in the usual course of business • Revaluation of the inventories of oil and gas for sale, reported by extraction companies and refineries • Raw material purchase costs • Cost of supplies • Goods purchased • Power and fuel expenses Material Expenses [SMAT] excludes: • Impairment/write-down/write-off/revaluation of inventories arising from a non-recurring (one-off) event (Gain/(Loss) on Valuation of Inventory [EVAI]) • Change in the value of raw materials stored arising in the normal course of business (Changes in Inventory [EIDS])

i.d: Private Company. Minority Interest [SMNI] represents the share of earnings/losses in subsidiaries that belong to shareholders other than the parent company when the parent company owns less than 100%, but more than 50%, of a subsidiary. Since the subsidiary's financials are consolidated by the company, this value is a negative number to represent the amount the company does not own. Applicable to all industries. Minority Interest [SMNI] includes: • Minority Interest – reported after income tax • Non-controlling interest – reported after income tax • Net income Attributable to Non Controlling Interest • Minority owners share of subsidiaries net income • Joint Venture results attributable to non controlling interest Minority Interest [SMNI] excludes: • Minority interest reported within other comprehensive income (OCI - Other - Net of Tax [XCON]) • Minority interest reported within total comprehensive income (OCI Total Comprehensive Income Attributable to Minority Interest [XCIM]) • Earnings allocated to general partners (Distribution to General Partners [CGPD]) • Dividends to preferred stockholders (Distribution for Preferential Shares [CPRD])

i.d: Private Company. Net Income After Minority Interests [SNIC] represents the as reported total net income/loss after provision for income taxes, equity in earnings, after-tax adjustments, discontinued operations, extraordinary items and minority interest, but before other adjustments to net income, preferred dividends and other distributions. This item is applicable to all industries.

i.d: Private Company. Net Income After Tax [SIAT] represents the as reported income/expense after all operating and non-operating income and expense, reserves, income taxes, but before equity in earnings, minority interest, extraordinary items, after-tax adjustments, discontinued operations and preferred dividends. Applicable to all industries. Net Income After Tax [SIAT] includes: • Profit/(loss) for the year from continuing operations • Net (loss)/profit from operations after income tax expense

i.d: Private Company. Net Income Before Minority Interest [SIBM] represents the sum of Income before Discontinued Operations and Extraordinary Items [SICO] and all after tax extraordinary items reported by the company (Gain/loss on Extraordinary Activities - after Tax [STEX]). If the statement is non-detailed Net Income before Minority Interest [SIBM] is equal to Net Income After Extraordinary Items [XNIX]. Applicable to all industries.

i.d: Private Company. Net Other Operating Income/Expense [SOIE] represents net operating income/expenses which are either not specified as being for plant hire, fixed asset rentals, depreciation/amortization, marketing, duties/taxes, exchange losses, research/development or exploration, or which may represent a combination of some or all of these items. Applicable to all industries.

i.d: Private Company. Non-Recurring Income/Expense - Non-Business Activities – Total [ENRE] represents the total net non-recurring income or losses, reported before taxes. Applicable to all industries. Non-Recurring Income/Expense - Non-Business Activities – Total [ENRE] includes: • One-off results of non-recurring events • Revaluation of biological assets, investments, financial assets, investment properties and other assets
i.i: A:1L A:AN A:AP A:FP A:FR A:FQ A:AQ A:FN A:1W A:31 A:FS A:AR A:32 A:AT A:AU A:33 A:34 A:35 A:36 A:37 A:FU A:FT A:10 A:39 A:3A A:AS A:2R A:BF A:BG A:BH A:BI A:BJ A:3C A:3B A:3F A:1X A:FV A:FX A:FW A:18 A:FZ A:FY A:AV I:17 I:50 A:2X A:KZ A:L0 A:L1 A:L2 A:L3 A:L4 A:L5 A:L6 A:5M A:2Y

i.d: Private Company. Normalized After Tax Profit [SNAT] represents the value of income/expense after all operating and non-operating income and expense, reserves, income taxes, but before equity in earnings, minority interest, extraordinary items, after-tax adjustments, discontinued operations and preferred dividends (Net Income After Tax [SIAT]) adjusted by the total value of non-recurring income or expenses (Total Non-Recurring Income/Expense - Non-business Activities [SGLN]). Applicable to all industries.
i.i: A:1L A:AN A:AP A:FP A:FR A:FQ A:AQ A:FN A:1W A:31 A:FS A:AR A:32 A:AT A:AU A:33 A:34 A:35 A:36 A:37 A:FU A:FT A:10 A:39 A:3A A:AS A:2R A:BF A:BG A:BH A:BI A:BJ A:3C A:3B A:3F A:1X A:FV A:FX A:FW A:18 A:FZ A:FY A:AV I:17 I:50 A:2X A:KZ A:L0 A:L1 A:L2 A:L3 A:L4 A:L5 A:L6 A:5M A:2Y

i.d: Private Company. Normalized Net Income - Bottom Line [SIBL] represents total net income/loss reported by the company after provision for income taxes, equity in earnings, after-tax adjustments, discontinued operations, extraordinary items and minority interest, but before other adjustments to net income, preferred dividends and other distributions (Income available to Common Shares [SNIS]) adjusted by the total value of non-recurring income or expenses (Total Non-Recurring Income/Expense - Non-business Activities [SGLN]). Applicable to all industries.
i.i: A:1L A:AN A:AP A:FP A:FR A:FQ A:AQ A:FN A:1W A:31 A:FS A:AR A:32 A:AT A:AU A:33 A:34 A:35 A:36 A:37 A:FU A:FT A:10 A:39 A:3A A:AS A:2R A:BF A:BG A:BH A:BI A:BJ A:3C A:3B A:3F A:1X A:FV A:FX A:FW A:18 A:FZ A:FY A:AV I:17 I:50 A:2X A:KZ A:L0 A:L1 A:L2 A:L3 A:L4 A:L5 A:L6 A:5M A:2Y

i.d: Private Company. Normalized Net Income from Continuing Operations [SNCO] represents the Income before Discontinued Operations and Extraordinary Items [SICO] adjusted by the total value of non-recurring income or expenses (Total Non-Recurring Income/Expense - Non-business Activities [SGLN])
i.i: A:1L A:AN A:AP A:FP A:FR A:FQ A:AQ A:FN A:1W A:31 A:FS A:AR A:32 A:AT A:AU A:33 A:34 A:35 A:36 A:37 A:FU A:FT A:10 A:39 A:3A A:AS A:2R A:BF A:BG A:BH A:BI A:BJ A:3C A:3B A:3F A:1X A:FV A:FX A:FW A:18 A:FZ A:FY A:AV I:17 I:50 A:2X A:KZ A:L0 A:L1 A:L2 A:L3 A:L4 A:L5 A:L6 A:5M A:2Y

i.d: Private Company. Normalized Pre-tax Profit [SNPX] represents pre-tax profit without the effect of unusual and extraordinary income/expense. Normalized Pre-tax Profit [SNPX] is a sum of: • Operating Profits Before Non-Recurring Income/Expense [SOPR] • Other Non-Operating Income/Expense - Total [SNEI] • Equity Earnings - Before Taxes Including Non-Recurring [SIQA] • Financing Income/Expense, Net - Total [SFIE] • Gains/Losses on Sale of Tangible and Intangible Fixed Assets [SFAS]

i.d: Private Company. Operating Expense – Total [SOET] represents total operating expense as reported by the company, which is reported in the gross profit or operating expense formats. Applicable to all industries. Operating Expense – Total [SOET] includes: • Total operating expenses

Operating Profits Before Non-Recurring Income & Expenses [SOPR] represents the as reported total operating income (revenues and operating income less operating costs) from a company’s primary/core operations, before non-recurring and non-operating items. This item is applicable to all industries.

i.d: Private Company. Operating Provisions [EOPR] represents any movement in operating provisions such as maintenance expenses and provisions for risks and charges. Applicable to all industries and may also be reported as part of the business and geographic segment information. Operating Provisions [EOPR] includes: • Provisions for risk and charges • Provisions for maintenance expense • Provisions for other operating expenses Operating Provisions [EOPR] excludes: • Provisions for bad debts (Bad Debt Written Off/Provision [EBDW]) • Provision for Decommissioning Fund and Environmental Obligations [EPDF] • Accretion of Site Closure and Reclamation Expenses [EASR]

i.d: Private Company. Other Adjustments After Taxes [COAN] represents other adjustments to net income reported after taxes but before equity in earnings, minority interest, extraordinary items, discontinued operations and preferred dividends. Applicable to all industries.
i.i: A:1L A:AN A:AP A:FP A:FR A:FQ A:AQ A:FN A:1W A:31 A:FS A:AR A:32 A:AT A:AU A:33 A:34 A:35 A:36 A:37 A:FU A:FT A:10 A:39 A:3A A:AS A:2R A:BF A:BG A:BH A:BI A:BJ A:3C A:3B A:3F A:1X A:FV A:FX A:FW A:18 A:FZ A:FY A:AV I:17 I:50 A:2X A:KZ A:L0 A:L1 A:L2 A:L3 A:L4 A:L5 A:L6 A:5M A:2Y

i.d: Private Company. Other Adjustments After Taxes - Total [SOAN] represents adjustments to net income reported after taxes but before equity in earnings, minority interest, extraordinary items, discontinued operations and preferred dividends. It includes Zakat, the impact of discontinued operations reported before taxes on total taxes payable for the period and adjustment of special reserve. This item includes also all rounding adjustments reported after tax. Other Adjustments After Taxes - Total [SOAN] represents is a sum of: • Other Adjustments After Taxes [COAN] • Rounding Adjustment Income Statement [IIII] • Estimated Tax Impact on Pre-tax Discontinued Operations [CETD] • After-tax Adjustments on Special Reserves [CASR]

i.d: Private Company. Other Adjustments to Net Income [COAJ] represents an adjustment applied to net earnings that is used to calculate a company’s earnings per share. When net income used for EPS computation is not clearly reported by a company, the difference between the net income reported and the net income required for EPS computation is calculated and classified as Other Adjustments to Net Income. This item is applicable to all industries and may also be reported as part of the business and geographic segment information. Other Adjustments to Net Income [COAJ] includes: • Warrant dividends • Warrant accretion • Pro Forma Adjustment Other Adjustments to Net Income [COAJ] excludes: • Dilution adjustment [CDAJ] • U.S. GAAP adjustment [CGAP] • Earnings distribution to general unlimited partners (Distribution for General Partners [CGPD]) • Accredited/declared/deemed/imputed dividends to preferred stocks; issuance of additional shares (preferred or common) in lieu of cash dividend to preferred stocks is considered to be equivalent to cash dividends to the preferred stock (Distribution for Preferential Shares [CPRD]) • After-tax adjustment that aren’t reported as adjustments for the computation of earnings per share, such as equity in earnings, estimated tax impact of pre-tax discontinued operations, Zakat, adjustments on special reserves and other adjustments after taxes

Other Cost of Goods Sold [EOCG] includes: • Write-down of inventories as part of normal operations Other Cost of Goods Sold [EOCG] excludes: • Impairment/write-down of inventories resulting from a non-recurring/one-off/exceptional event (Gain/(Loss) on Valuation of Inventory [EVAI])

Applicable to Industrial, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. Other Cost of Goods Sold - Total [SCOS] includes: • Write-down of inventories as part of normal operations Lease Operating Expenses (Oil and Gas Industry) [ELOE] • Mine decommissioning/rehabilitation provisions • Call costs • Monthly wholesale access fees • Costs associated with transmission, uplink and telemetry facilities • Any other airline industry specific items • Operating lease rentals • Sub-lease rental • Related provisions • Traffic servicing • Navigation fees • Handling charges • Terminal, landing and parking fees • Third-party project expenses Other Cost of Goods Sold - Total [SCOS] excludes: • Impairment/write-down of inventories resulting from a non-recurring/one-off/exceptional event (Gain/(Loss) on Valuation of Inventory [EVAI]) • Exploration and evaluation expenses • Depreciation and amortization in the cost of goods sold related to direct extraction expenses (Depreciation/Amortization in Cost of Revenues/Cost of Goods Sold [EDAC]) • Production Taxes and Royalty Expenses [EPTE] • Transmission and other network costs (Network Costs [ENWC]) • Any other airline industry specific items

i.d: Private Company. Provision for Income Tax [TTAX] represents all taxes on the basis of profits that may be owed to federal, state and/or foreign government. Provision for Income Tax [TTAX] includes: • Income Tax Expense • Corporate Income Tax • If the company reported a single line of tax as current tax (Current Tax - Total [VCTR]) / deferred tax (Deferred Tax - Total [VDTR]), same would be considered as Provision for Income Tax [TTAX] on the face of the statement • Income taxes for federal, state and local authorities of current tax or deferred tax • Charges in lieu of income taxes • Income taxes paid by consolidated subsidiaries • Income taxes paid by foreign subsidiaries • Income taxes recovered • Charges equivalent to investment tax credit Provision for Income Tax [TTAX] excludes: • Domestic International Sales Corporation taxes • Ad Valorem taxes • Windfall profit taxes • Taxes other than income • General and services taxes • Excise/sales taxes, VAT (Excise Taxes Receipts (Other Taxes) [REXT]) • Business taxes, franchise taxes, property taxes, production taxes, stamp duties and licensing fees (Selling, General & Administration Expenses [ESGA] for industrial and insurance, property and Other Taxes [EPOT] for utilities)

i.d: Private Company. Revenue Taxes [SEXT] represents a government-levied tax on the manufacture, sale, or consumption of goods and services included in the sale price, collected by the seller, and returned to the government. The tax can be imposed at any trade level and can either be a specific tax or a value-added tax (percentage of value). Thomson Reuters uses excise taxes receipts only when receipts of excise taxes are clearly identified as revenue in the income statement of a company. (In most cases, this item appears twice, once as income (collected from customers) and as expense (paid to the government). Applicable to Industrial companies. Revenue Taxes [SEXT] includes: • Sales and excise taxes and duties reported outside gross revenues • Excise/sales taxes, VAT • Sales Tax • Business Tax • Operating Tax • Consumption Tax • VAT • Coal resource tax (Coal business) • General and services tax • Windfall profit taxes • Ad valorem taxes • Domestic international sales corporation taxes Revenue Taxes [SEXT] excludes: • Excise taxes reported within gross revenues (before subtracting from the gross value of sales) (Gross Turnover [RREV]) • Sales allowances for clients and distributors, sales returns, and other adjustment decreasing the value of gross sales (Allowances, Returns, and Other Adjustments [RSRT])

i.d: Private Company. Total Cost of Revenues [SCREV] represents the total value of costs of revenue including costs for operations and maintenance of power generating plants by electric utility companies, and maintenance of distribution facilities by utility companies. Applicable to Industrial, Property, Investment and Other Financial companies. Total Cost of Revenues [SCREV] includes: • Depreciation of power plants, transmission/distribution facilities (may be included in Operations and maintenance [EDOE] if not disclosed separately) • Amortization of nuclear fuel (may be included in Operations and maintenance [EDOE] if not disclosed separately) • Cost of repair/maintenance of vehicles for power distributions • Expenses incurred in operating and maintenance of power plants and distribution facilities including fuel expenses unless itemized by the company • Cost of revenue generated by the financing arm of a manufacturing company Total Cost of Revenues [SCREV] excludes: • Fuel expenses when itemized by the company (Fuel Expense [EFEX]) • Depreciation of power plants, transmission/distribution facilities if disclosed separately • Amortization of nuclear fuel if disclosed separately

i.d: Private Company. Total Depreciation & Amortization (Combined) [STDAE] represents the maximum value of combined depreciation and amortization reported by the company in the income statement, cash flow or notes. It is used in the calculation of ratios and analytics such as Earnings Before Interest, Taxes, Depreciation & Amortization (EBITDA). Applicable to all industries. Total Depreciation & Amortization (Combined) [STDAE] includes the highest of the following values reported by the company: • Depreciation & Amortization [VDAE] • Depreciation & Amortization [EDAE] + Depreciation & Amortization in Cost of Revenues/ Cost of Goods Sold [EDAC] + Depreciation & Amortization in SGA [EDAS] + Depreciation & Amortization in Research and Development [EDAR] • Depreciation and Amortization - to Reconcile [ODEA] • Depreciation, Depletion, Impairment and Amortization - Total [XDIA] Total Depreciation and Amortization (Combined) [STDAE] excludes: • Combined depreciation/amortization reported in sources other than income statement, cash flow or notes (such as business or geographic segments) • Depreciation reported specifically by the company (Total Depreciation of Tangible Assets [TDEP]) • Total amortization of all intangible assets, reported specifically by the company (Total Amortization of Intangible Assets (including Goodwill) [TAMI]) • Amortization of goodwill, reported specifically by the company (Total Depreciation of Goodwill [TAMA]) • Amortization of intangible assets other than goodwill, reported specifically by the company (Total Amortization of Intangible Assets (excluding Goodwill) [TAMO])

Total Gross Revenue from Business Activities [SREV] represents gross receipts from the sales of products and services, before trade discounts, excise taxes, and sales returns and allowances. This item is applicable to industrial companies and may also be reported as part of the business and geographic segment information. Total Gross Revenue from Business Activities [SREV] excludes: • Total revenue from goods and services (Revenue from Goods and Services - Total (No b/d) [RNTU]) • Total Revenue [XTLR] • Net sales after excise tax receipts and sales returns and allowances (Revenue Sales of Goods and Services [RNTS]) • Excise tax receipts (Excise Taxes Receipts (Other Taxes) [REXT]) • Sales returns and allowances (Allowances, Returns, and Other Adjustments [RSRT]) • Specific net revenues reported by utility companies from electric (Revenue from Electric Operations [REOP]), gas (Revenue from Gas Operations [RGOP], water (Revenue from Water Operations [RWAT], steam (Revenue from Steam Operations [RSOP] and other utility operations (Revenue from Other Utility Operation [ROUR], as well as non-utility revenues reported by a utility company (Revenue from Non-Utility Business [RNUR]) • Islamic Income [ISIN] • Royalty Income – Business [RROI] • Hotel revenue (Hotel Revenue [RHRV], Hotel Revenue - Rooms [RHRR], Hotel Revenue - Hotel Lease Income [RHRL], Hotel Revenue - Food and Beverages [RHRF], Hotel Revenues - Other [RHRO]) • Rental, tenant service reimbursement and other rental-related income (Gross Rental Income and Related Income [RRRI], Tenant Service Charge Reimbursements [RTSR], Gross Rental Income [RGRI]) • Property Related Operating Revenue - Other [RPRO] • Property Related Operating Revenue - Total [RRPT] • Property Development Revenue [RPDR] • Property Management Services Revenue [RPMS] • Other Revenue from Business Related Activities [ROBR]

i.d: Private Company. Total Non-interest Financial Income/Expense [SNIF] represents the total value of non-interest expense. It includes realised and unrealised gains and losses recorded as a result of foreign exchange fluctuations, gains and losses on the sale of investments, dividend income and accretion of the costs that an extraction company will incur in the future, for the closure of a mine and restoring the natural environment to its previous shape. Total Non-interest Financial Income/Expense [SNIF] is the sum of: • Other Net Non-interest Financial Income/Expense [SINO] • Non-interest Financial Income/Expense - Total - no b/d [EINU] • Foreign Exchange Gain/Loss [EIFX] • Dividend/Investment Income [EIDT] • Gain/Loss on the Sale of Investments Held for Sale, Maturity and Trading [EGIT] • Accretion of site closure and reclamation expenses [EASR] • Amortization of Deferred Financing Costs [EADF]

i.d: Private Company. Dividends Provided or Paid – Common [SDCM] represents the cash amount of dividends paid or payable to the holders of common stock (i.e. shares participating in the company’s earnings) and attributable to a specific accounting period. The value is populated as reported by the company. If the information is not available in the financial report, Thomson Reuters analysts do not make assumptions about this value. Applicable to all industries. Dividends Provided or Paid – Common [SDCM] includes: • Dividends to ordinary shares • Dividends to participating preference shares which have common characteristics and participate in the earnings of the company (e.g. most preferred shares in Brazil, Vorzugsaktien in Austria and Germany, Savings Shares/Azioni di Risparmio and Preference Shares/Azioni Privilegiate in Italy) • Final dividends to common shares if disclosed in the financial report • Proposed dividends to common shares if final dividend has not been confirmed, e.g. declared initially by the board of directors and subject to voting of the annual general meeting of shareholders (AGM) Dividends Provided or Paid – Common [SDCM] excludes: • Fixed dividends paid to the holders of preferred shares not participating in the earnings of the company (deducted from net income and collected as Distribution for Preferential Shares [CPRD])

i.d: Private Company. Full-Time Employees [SETL] represents the number of full-time employees, as reported, as of the fiscal period end date. If full time equivalents (FTE’s) are available for collection, this value is preferred over total number not translated into full-time equivalents. Applicable to all industries. Full-Time Employees (Period End) [SETL] includes: • All full-time employees that are on the company payroll: employees, workers, apprentices, trainees, etc. • Full time equivalents (FTEs) of full-time employees, if reported (e.g. consolidated number of employees which includes pro rata the number of employees in companies consolidated proportionally) • Estimated or approximate number of full time employees if precise number is not reported • Total number of full-time employees (not full time equivalents) if the company does not report full time equivalents • Total number of employees (including part-time employees) if the company does not report full-time and part-time employees separately reported as of period end date. Full-Time Employees (Period End) [SETL] excludes: • Seasonal and temporary workers as well as interns (both full time and part time), unless not possible to exclude them from the reported number • Contractors (external suppliers of services) • Company’s directors • Employees of associated or affiliated companies which are not consolidated in the group report • Full-time agency employees hired for clients by companies in the personnel services business • Number of part-time employees if the company differentiates the types of employees and reports them separately (Part-Time Employees (Period End) [MPTL]) • Full time employees reported as of a date different than period end date, falling between the previous period end date and current report’s filing date (collected as Full-Time Employees (Last Reported) [META] with Employees (As of Date) [METD]) • Average number of full time employees (Average Number of Employees [MEAV])

i.d: Private Company. Full-Time Employees (Period End) [METL] represents the number of full-time employees, as reported, as of the fiscal period end date. If full time equivalents (FTE’s) are available for collection, this value is preferred over total number not translated into full-time equivalents. Full-Time Employees (Period End) [METL] is applicable to all industries. Full-Time Employees (Period End) [METL] includes: • All full-time employees that are on the company payroll: employees, workers, apprentices, trainees, etc. • Full time equivalents (FTEs) of full-time employees, if reported (e.g. consolidated number of employees which includes pro rata the number of employees in companies consolidated proportionally) • Estimated or approximate number of full time employees if precise number is not reported • Total number of full-time employees (not full time equivalents) if the company does not report full time equivalents • Total number of employees (including part-time employees) if the company does not report full-time and part-time employees separately reported as of period end date. Full-Time Employees (Period End) [METL] excludes: • Seasonal and temporary workers as well as interns (both full time and part time), unless not possible to exclude them from the reported number • Contractors (external suppliers of services) • Company’s directors • Employees of associated or affiliated companies which are not consolidated in the group report • Full-time agency employees hired for clients by companies in the personnel services business • Number of part-time employees if the company differentiates the types of employees and reports them separately (classified as Part-Time Employees [MPTL]) • Full time employees reported as of a date different than period end date, falling between the previous period end date and current report’s filing date (collected as Full-Time Employees (Last Reported) [META] with Employees (As of Date) [METD]) • Average number of full time employees (Average Number of Employees [MEAV])
